{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Taiwan}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan\n| map1 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Free area of the Republic of China.svg\n| legend1 = Confirmed cases breakdown by municipalities and counties\n{{columns-list|\n{{legend|#808080|0}}\n{{legend|#ffd5d5|1}}\n{{legend|#ffaaaa|2~4}}\n{{legend|#ff8080|5~9}}\n{{legend|#ff5555|10~19}}\n{{legend|#ff2a2a|20~29}}\n{{legend|#ff0000|30~49}}\n{{legend|#d40000|50~74}}\n{{legend|#aa0000|75+}}\n}}\n| map2 = COVID-19 outbreak Taiwan per capita cases map.svg\n| legend2 = Confirmed cases per million residents by subdivision\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Taiwan]]\n| first_case = [[Taoyuan International Airport]]\n| arrival_date = 21 January 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=21|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China\n| recovery_cases = 50<ref name=\"cdc.gov.tw/En\">[https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En Taiwan Centers for Disease Control]</ref><ref name=\"Dash\"/><ref name=\"CTCTP\"/>\n| deaths = 5<ref name=\"cdc.gov.tw/En\"/><ref name=\"Dash\">[https://coronaboard.com Corona Dash Board]</ref><ref name=\"CTCTP\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 355<ref name=\"cdc.gov.tw/En\"/><ref name=\"Dash\"/><ref name=\"CTCTP\">[https://www.coronatracker.com/country/tw Corona Tracker Overview]</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En\n}}\nAs of mid-March 2020, [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) has had a more moderate impact in [[Taiwan]] than in many neighboring countries, with relatively few infections overall.<ref name=20200304voanews>{{cite news |last1=Jennings |first1=Ralph |title=Why Taiwan Has Just 42 Coronavirus Cases while Neighbors Report Hundreds or Thousands |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/why-taiwan-has-just-42-coronavirus-cases-while-neighbors-report |accessdate=5 March 2020 |publisher=Voice of America |date=4 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Duff-Brown\">{{cite web |last1=Duff-Brown |first1=Beth |title=How Taiwan Used Big Data, Transparency and a Central Command to Protect Its People from Coronavirus |url=https://healthpolicy.fsi.stanford.edu/news/how-taiwan-used-big-data-transparency-central-command-protect-its-people-coronavirus |publisher=Freeman Spogli Institute for International Studies and the Stanford School of Medicine |accessdate=5 March 2020 |date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera2003070343\">{{cite news |last1=Hale |first1=Erin |title=How to control the spread of the coronavirus: Lessons from Taiwan |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/taiwan-reins-spread-coronavirus-countries-stumble-200307034353325.html |accessdate=11 March 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The first case was announced on 21 January 2020. \n\nThe Taiwanese government integrated data from the [[Healthcare in Taiwan|national healthcare system]], immigration, and customs authorities to aid in the identification and response to the virus. Government efforts are coordinated through the National Health Command Center (NHCC) of the [[Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)|Taiwan Centers for Disease Control]], established to aid in [[disaster management]] for epidemics following the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|2004 SARS outbreak]].<ref name=\"WangNgBrook\">{{cite journal |last1=Wang |first1=C. Jason |last2=Ng |first2=Chun Y. |last3=Brook |first3=Robert H. |title=Response to COVID-19 in Taiwan: Big Data Analytics, New Technology, and Proactive Testing |journal=JAMA |date=3 March 2020 |doi=10.1001/jama.2020.3151|pmid=32125371 }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' states that Taiwan engaged in 124 discrete action items to prevent the spread of the disease, including early screening of flights from Mainland China and the tracking of individual cases.<ref name=vox21171722/><ref name=Duff-Brown/>\n\nTaiwan's handling of the outbreak has received international praise for its effectiveness in quarantining the people and by using the \"electronic fence\" to slow down the virus, despite being unable to gather WHO information due to being barred by China, and is seen as the model for other countries to learn from.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/20/taiwans-electronic-fence-monitor-for-those-quarantined-raises-privacy-concerns/|date=20 March 2020|title=Taiwan's \u2018electronic fence\u2019 monitor for those quarantined raises privacy concerns|work=[[New York Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/why-taiwan-has-just-42-coronavirus-cases-while-neighbors-report|date=4 March 2020|title=Why Taiwan Has Just 42 Coronavirus Cases while Neighbors Report Hundreds or Thousands|publisher=[[VOA News]]}}</ref> As of 29 March, 29,915 tests had been conducted in Taiwan with the vast majority not confirming a coronavirus diagnosis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En|title=Home}}</ref>\n\nStarting 19 March foreign nationals were barred from entering Taiwan, with some exceptions, such as those carrying out the term of a business contract, holding valid Alien Resident Certificates, diplomatic credentials, or other official documentation and special permits.<ref name=\"barentry\">{{Cite news | url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003180007 |first1=Ming-hsuan|last1=Chang|first2=Frances|last2=Huang|first3=Christie|last3=Chen|title = Taiwan to bar entry of foreign nationals to combat COVID-19 (Update)|agency=Central News Agency}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Taiwan medical cases chart}}\n\nOn 21 January, the first case in Taiwan was confirmed in a 50-year-old woman who just returned to [[Taoyuan International Airport]] from her teaching job in Wuhan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan confirms 1st Wuhan coronavirus case (update) |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202001210019 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=TaiwanCDC21Jan2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En/Bulletin/Detail/pVg_jRVvtHhp94C6GShRkQ?typeid=158|title= Taiwan timely identifies first imported case of 2019 novel coronavirus infection returning from Wuhan, China through onboard quarantine; Central Epidemic Command Center (CECC) raises travel notice level for Wuhan, China to Level 3: Warning |publisher=Taiwan Centers for Disease Control |date=21 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> She reported on her own initiative and was hospitalised without formal domestic entry.<ref name=TaiwanCDC21Jan2020 /> The first domestic case was diagnosed in Taiwan on 28 January.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Ming-hsuan |last2=Low |first2=Y.F. |title=WUHAN VIRUS / Taiwan confirms first domestic case of Wuhan coronavirus |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202001285001 |accessdate=28 January 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=28 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128150445/https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202001285001 |archive-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first death in Taiwan was confirmed on 16 February involving a man in his 60s who had [[Hepatitis B]] and [[diabetes]].<ref name=\"d1\">{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Ming-hsuan |last2=Yeh |first2=Joseph |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan reports first death from coronavirus infection (update) |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002160012 |accessdate=17 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=16 February 2020}}</ref> A woman in Taiwan was reported to have tested positive for novel coronavirus on 19 February 2020, though she had not traveled outside of Taiwan for two years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Low |first2=Y.F. |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan reports new coronavirus case with unknown origin |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002200003 |accessdate=20 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=20 February 2020}}</ref> Five new cases of coronavirus were reported in Taiwan on 29 February 2020, four of which marked the first transmission of the disease in a hospital setting.<ref name=\"hospitalcluster\">{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Ming-hsuang |last2=Mazzetta |first2=Matthew |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan records first COVID-19 hospital cluster cases (update) |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002290008 |accessdate=29 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=29 February 2020}}</ref> Taiwan's fiftieth case of coronavirus was confirmed on 13 March 2020, an American expatriate who hosted four United States citizens at his home in Taiwan.<ref name=\"50usatwn\">{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Ming-hsuan |last2=Wu |first2=Hsin-yun |last3=Hsu |first3=Elizabeth |title=CORONAVIRUS / American man confirmed as Taiwan's 50th COVID-19 case (update) |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003130013 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, three new cases of coronavirus were confirmed to have been imported from Europe.<ref name=\"53eurtwn\">{{cite news |last1=Wu |first1=Hsin-yun |last2=Chang |first2=Ming-hsuan |last3=Mazzetta |first3=Matthew |title=CORONAVIRUS / COVID-19 infections rise to 53 in Taiwan with confirmation of 3 new cases |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003140009 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> A Taiwanese national aboard the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' tested positive on 6 February.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yang |first1=Ming-chu |last2=Chen |first2=Wei-ting |last3=Lim |first3=Emerson |last4=Chiang |first4=Yi-ching |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwanese tests positive for coronavirus on quarantined cruise ship |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202002060007 |accessdate=6 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=6 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206150412/https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202002060007 |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> As of 19 February, five Taiwanese nationals aboard the ship tested positive.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Flor |last2=Chen |first2=Wei-ting |title=One more Taiwanese on cruise liner confirmed with coronavirus |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002190018 |accessdate=19 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=19 February 2020}}</ref> Two Taiwanese who fell ill on the ''Diamond Princess'' were discharged from Japanese hospitals in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Lee |first2=Hsin-Yin |title=2 Taiwanese coronavirus patients discharged from hospital in Japan |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002260015 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The nineteen other Taiwanese passengers on the ''Diamond Princess'' were quarantined in Taiwan until 7 March 2020. All tested negative for coronavirus, and were released.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Chien-pang |last2=Chen |first2=Christie |last3=Huang |first3=Frances |title=WUHAN VIRUS / Taiwan evacuees from Diamond Princess released from quarantine (update) |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003070004 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The [[index case]] for coronavirus in Taiwan recovered from the disease and was discharged from hospital on 6 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Ko |first2=Lin |title=First Wuhan virus patient in Taiwan discharged from hospital |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002060013 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=6 February 2020}}</ref> Approximately a week later, a second Taiwanese national, the tenth case of coronavirus, had also recovered.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Ming-hsuan |last2=Ko |first2=Lin |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan may soon discharge second recovering Wuhan virus patient |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002100014 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> As of 2 April 2020, 50 people have recovered from coronavirus in Taiwan.<ref name=\"339r50\">{{cite news |last1=Chiang |first1=Yi-ching |title=CORONAVIRUS/Taiwan adds 10 new COVID-19 cases, bringing total to 339 |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202004020010https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202004020010 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 15 March, Taiwan announced six new cases, all imported.  Health authorities are tracing contacts of these persons.  Taiwan's health minister has advised people to remain in Taiwan and not to travel at all.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan/taiwan-reports-six-new-coronavirus-cases-in-largest-single-day-rise-all-imported-idUSKBN21207K Taiwan reports six new coronavirus cases in largest single-day rise, all imported], Reuters, 15 March 2020.</ref> On 20 March 2020, Taiwan reported 27 new cases, the highest single-day increase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En/Bulletin/Detail/gpQ2wZ5l2v9kVANW-a1p7A?typeid=158|title=CECC confirms a total of 27 more COVID-19 cases, including 24 imported cases|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)|Taiwan Centers for Disease Control]]}}</ref> The second death linked to coronavirus in Taiwan was announced on 20 March, and involved a man in his 80s, who had no recent travel history, but did have hypertension, diabetes and relied on kidney dialysis.<ref name=\"d2\">{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Flor |last2=Chang |first2=Ming-hsuan |last3=Wu |first3=Hsin-yun |title=CORONAVIRUS/Taiwan records second COVID-19 death |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003200017 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The death of a guide who had led tours to Austria and the Czech Republic was reported on 29 March.<ref name=\"d3\">{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Huang |first2=Frances |title=Taiwan records third COVID-19 death |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003300004 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, two Taiwanese nationals who had traveled to Spain, were reported to have died of coronavirus.<ref name=\"d4&5\">{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Yeh |first2=Joseph |title=CORONAVIRUS/Taiwan records two more COVID-19 deaths, eight new cases |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003300014 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 4 April, there are 355 confirmed cases, including five deaths.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Hsin-Yin |title=CORONAVIRUS/Taiwan adds 7 new cases of COVID-19, total up to 355 |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202004040004 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"d4&5\"/> Among the confirmed cases is a Taiwanese man in his 50s who was fined [[New Taiwan dollar|NT$]]300,000 for failure to report his symptoms and attempting to conceal his subsequent activities, leading to a potential contamination incident at a [[ballroom]] in [[Kaohsiung]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Shwu-fen |last2=Hsu |first2=Elizabeth |title=WUHAN VIRUS / Taiwanese man to be fined for not reporting viral symptoms |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202001250011 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=25 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126025331/https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202001250011 |archive-date=26 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Cases===\n<div style=\"overflow-x:a