xisTitle=\n | yAxisTitle=\n | colors = blue\n}}</div>\n\nImported cases: 298; Locally transmitted cases: 50\n\n== Preventive measures==\n[[File:Taiwan -i---i- (49436628738).jpg|thumb|Surgical masks used by people in Taiwan]]\n[[File:Masks sold in Taiwan.jpg|thumb|Surgical masks and other medical equipment sold out in Taiwan]]\n===Before first case reported===\nOn 31 December 2019, [[Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)|Taiwan Centers for Disease Control]] (CDC) implemented inspection measures for inbound flights from [[Wuhan]], China in response to reports of an unidentified outbreak.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?unit=2,6,10,15,18&post=168773|title=CDC implements extra inspection measures for Wuhan flights|agency=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of China|date=2 January 2020|website=Taiwan Today|url-status=live|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> The passengers of all such flights were inspected by health officials before disembarking.<ref name=\":0\" /> A six-year-old passenger who transferred in Wuhan and developed a fever was closely monitored by CDC.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3848765|title=Passenger from China's Wuhan develops fever amid pneumonia fears|work=Taiwan News|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> At this time, there was alleged to be 27 cases of the new pneumonia in Wuhan.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nBy 5 January 2020, the Taiwan CDC began monitoring all individuals who had travelled to Wuhan within fourteen days and exhibited a fever or symptoms of upper respiratory tract infections. These people were screened for 26 known pathogens, including [[SARS]] and [[Middle East respiratory syndrome]], and those testing positive were quarantined.<ref name=\"WangNgBrook\"/>\n\nOn 20 January, the government deemed the risk posed by the outbreak sufficient to activate the {{ill|Central Epidemic Command Center|zh|\u4e2d\u592e\u6d41\u884c\u75ab\u60c5\u6307\u63ee\u4e2d\u5fc3}} (CECC).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chiang |first1=Yi-ching |last2=Wen |first2=Kuei-hsiang |last3=Wang |first3=Cheng-chung |title=CORONAVIRUS / How Taiwan has been able to keep COVID-19 at bay |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003160019 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"cecctt\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=I-chia |last2=Shan |first2=Shelley |title=Epidemic response command center set up |url=http://taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2020/01/21/2003729605 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNA20Jan\">{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Weiting |script-title=zh:\u53f0\u7063\u9632\u7bc4\u5099\u6230\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e \u6210\u7acb\u4e09\u7d1a\u75ab\u60c5\u6307\u63ee\u4e2d\u5fc3 |url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202001205004.aspx |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=cna.com.tw |agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |date=20 January 2020 |language=zh-TW}}</ref> Originally established as a level 3 government entity,<ref name=\"cecctt\"/> the CECC was promoted to level 1 on 28 February.<ref name=taipeitimes2003731749>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Sean |title=Virus Outbreak: Su, eyeing 'good offense,' promotes CECC |url=http://taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2020/02/28/2003731749 |accessdate=6 March 2020 |date=28 February 2020}}</ref> The CECC has coordinated government responses across areas including logistics for citizens on the [[Diamond Princess (ship)|''Diamond Princess'']], disinfection of public spaces around schools, and providing daily briefings with [[Chen Shih-chung]], the Minister of Health and Welfare.<ref name=\"WangNgBrook\"/>\n\n===After first case reported===\nAfter the first case of the coronavirus was reported on 21 January, the [[Government of the Republic of China|Taiwanese government]] announced a temporary ban on the export of face masks for a month on 24 January to secure a supply of masks for its own citizens;<ref name=\"BBCTW06Feb2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51363132 |title=Coronavirus: Does China have enough face masks to meet its needs? |date=6 February 2020 |website=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209150926/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51363132 |archive-date=9 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters27Jan2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-ups-chinese-visitor-curbs-to-stop-mask-exports-idUSKBN1ZQ1C6 |title=Taiwan ups Chinese visitor curbs, to stop mask exports |date=27 January 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206141642/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-ups-chinese-visitor-curbs-to-stop-mask-exports-idUSKBN1ZQ1C6 |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> on 13 February, this was extended until the end of April.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://udn.com/news/story/120958/4341405 |title=\u56e0\u61c9\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e \u653f\u5e9c\u53e3\u7f69\u7981\u51fa\u53e3\u5f37\u5236\u5fb5\u7528\u5c07\u5ef6\u9577\u52304\u6708\u5e95 |date=13 February 2020 |work=United Daily News |accessdate=13 February 2020 |author1=\u5468\u4f51\u653f |author2=\u8cf4\u4e8e\u699b |language=zh}}</ref> On 6 February, the government instituted a mask rationing system, requiring citizens to present their [[National Health Insurance (Taiwan)|National Health Insurance]] card.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ku |first1=Chuan |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan approves new rationing system for surgical masks |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002030019 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=taipeitimes2003730707>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Liang-sheng |title=Virus Outbreak: Mask policy needs to be changed: KMT legislator |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/10/2003730707 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> Prior to its implementation, the system was extended to holders of the [[Alien Resident Certificate]], and people with valid entry permits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Mazzetta |first2=Matthew |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Government tweaks mask rationing plan to include all foreign nationals |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002050024 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=5 February 2020}}</ref> People with odd-numbered identity documents were permitted to buy masks on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays; those with even-numbered identity documents were to buy masks on Tuesdays, Thursdays, and Saturdays; anyone is allowed to buy masks on Sundays. Adults were allowed to buy two masks each visit and children four, with the restriction that a minimum of seven days must elapse since the last purchase. The date restriction for children under thirteen years of age was revoked on 27 February.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Ming-hsuan |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=New rules for children's mask purchase to come into effect Thursday |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002250016 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wu |first1=Hsin-yun |last2=Hau |first2=Hsueh-ching |last3=Chen |first3=Chi-feng |last4=Ku |first4=Chuan |last5=Yeh |first5=Joseph |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Over 1.4&nbsp;million surgical masks sold on first day of new rationing system |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002060019 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=6 February 2020}}</ref> Starting 5 March, adults were permitted to buy three masks weekly, and the children's quota was raised to five.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Yeh |first2=Joseph |title=WUHAN VIRUS/New rules to boost weekly face mask purchase quota |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003020017 |accessdate=2 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=2 March 2020}}</ref> Masks were available for pre-order online from 12 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ku |first1=Chuan |last2=Chang |first2=Ming-hsuan |last3=Yeh |first3=Joseph |title=WUHAN VIRUS / New online sales of surgical masks begin |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003120008 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In April, the mask rationing system is to be revised, so that adults could buy nine masks every two weeks. From 9 April, the specific date restrictions are to be removed. In addition, Taiwanese nationals can send 30 masks every two months overseas to first or second-degree relatives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=I-chia |title=Virus Outbreak: Rules eased to allow sending masks abroad |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/03/31/2003733720 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Chang |first2=Hsiung-feng |last3=Hsu |first3=Elizabeth |title=CORONAVIRUS/More masks, easier access coming in April under rationing program |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003300019 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Taiwan's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] assumed responsibility for distribution of masks to families of diplomats.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Emerson |title=Young children of foreign diplomats to receive rationed face masks |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002210008 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=21 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 2 February 2020, Taiwan's Central Epidemic Command Center postponed the opening of primary and secondary schools until 25 February (originally 11 February).<ref name=\"TWCDC02Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En/Bulletin/Detail/ZXg7cwUw7JlpVwftHatGKw?typeid=158 |title=In response to the outbreak of 2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) in China, Central Epidemic Command Center (CECC) decides that all primary and secondary schools postpone first day of spring semester until 2 weeks later |date=2 February 2020 |website=Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)}}</ref><ref name=\"FTW02Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002020016 |title=School opening postponed to Feb. 25 due to coronavirus |date=2 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207021103/https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002020016 |archive-date=7 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In early February 2020 Taiwan's Central Epidemic Command Center requested the mobilization of the [[Taiwanese Armed Forces]] to contain the spread of the virus and to build up the defenses against it. Soldiers were dispatched to the factory floors of major mask manufacturers to help staff the 62 additional mask production lines being set up at the time.<ref name=taiwannews3869320>{{cite news |first1=Tzu-ti |last1=Huang |title=Taiwan pledges military aid to boost mask supply |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3869320 |work=Taiwan News |accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> In early March, Taiwan's average production of surgical face masks reached 9.2&nbsp;million per day.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202003090013 |title=Taiwan mask output to hit 10 million per day by next week: minister |agency=Central News Agency |date=9 March 2020 |author1=Wu Po-wei |author2=Lee Wan-lin |author3=Ko Lin}}</ref>\n[[File:\u9678\u8ecd\u7b2c\u516b\u8ecd\u571839\u5316\u5b78\u5175\u7fa4\u5354\u52a9\u9810\u9632\u6027\u6d88\u6bd2 01.jpg|thumb|Disinfection against coronavirus]]\nThe [[Taiwan Tobacco and Liquor Corporation]] and the [[Taiwan Sugar Corporation]] increased production of 75 percent alcohol for use in sanitation.<ref name=taipeitimes2003730706>{{cite news |last1=Xie |first1=Dennis |title=Virus Outbreak: Taisugar, TTL ordered to produce more 75% alcohol |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/10/2003730706 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> On 25 February 2020, the Heping Women and Children's Hospital, a branch of the {{ill|Taipei City Hospital|zh|\u81fa\u5317\u5e02\u7acb\u806f\u5408\u91ab\u9662}}, was specially designated to care for patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liang |first1=Pei-chi |last2=Wang |first2=Shu-fen |last3=Wu |first3=Po-wei |last4=Huang |first4=Frances |title=Taipei City Hospital Heping branch designated as COVID-19 hospital |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002250025 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=25 February 2020}}</ref> From 4\u201331 March, the export of digital thermometers is to be banned.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wu |first1=Chia-rung |last2=Yeh |first2=Joseph |title=Taiwan bans export of digital thermometers until end of March |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202003040012 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=4 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, the [[Tsai Ing-wen]] presidential administration announced that Makalot Industrial and other Taiwanese companies would begin domestic mass production of protective gowns, ending a reliance on American imports from [[DuPont]] during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yeh |first1=Su-ping |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=CORONAVIRUS / Taiwan now making home-grown protective gowns: president |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202003160022 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Special Act on COVID-19 Prevention, Relief and Restoration]] was passed by the [[Legislative Yuan]] on 25 February 2020,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Yang-yu |last2=Yeh |first2=Joseph |title=Law to cope with coronavirus impact clears legislative floor |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202002250010 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=25 February 2020}}</ref> followed by a special budget for coronavirus expenses on 13 March 2020.<ref name=\"1332020clear\">{{cite news |last1=Fan |first1=Cheng-hsiang |last2=Wang |first2=Yang-yu |last3=Huang |first3=Frances |title=NT$60 billion budget to cope with coronavirus clears Legislature |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202003130014 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 14 March, persons returning to Taiwan from most of Europe, plus persons who have transferred through China, Hong Kong, Macau, and Dubai, must quarantine in-home for 14 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/coronavirus-travel-restrictions.html?searchResultPosition=1|title=Coronavirus Travel Restrictions, Across the Globe|work=The New York Times|date=18 March 2020}}</ref> As of 17 March, foreign nationals permitted in the country, namely, those who hold Alien Resident Certificates or who are on urgent diplomatic, business or other special missions, can rent a room in a public quarantine center.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?unit=2&post=173589|title=FAQ: Taiwan's 14-day quarantine requirements|publisher=Taiwan Today|date=18 March 2020|agency=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of China}}</ref> On 20 March, the CECC has raised global travel notice to level 3; Taiwanese citizens are advised to avoid all nonessential travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En/Bulletin/Detail/qaBvfAzLOukWMMGyNubKWw?typeid=158|title= CECC raises travel notice for all countries to Level 3: Warning; advises against all nonessential travel|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)|Taiwan Centers for Disease Control]]}}</ref> On 31 March, transportation and communications minister [[Lin Chia-lung]] announced that all passengers on trains and intercity buses were required to wear masks, as were people at highway rest stops. The [[Taiwan High Speed Rail Corporation]] installed thermal cameras at entrances to all twelve high speed rail stations. The [[Taiwan Railways Administration]] did the same for every one of its 239 stations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hsiao |first1=Yu-hsin |last2=Hetherington |first2=William |title=Virus Outbreak: Masks required for train passengers |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/04/01/2003733786 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The CECC stated on 3 April that passengers who refuse to wear masks after being asked to do so would be assessed a fine of NT$3,000 to NT$15,000, as stipulated by the Communicable Disease Control Act (\u50b3\u67d3\u75c5\u9632\u6cbb\u6cd5).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Chia-nan |title=Virus Outbreak: Fines authorized for unmasked riders |url=https://taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2020/04/04/2003733965 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Travel notices===\nDue to the coronavirus outbreak, Level 3 travel alerts have been issued by Taiwan for every country/region globally.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Huang |first1=Sunrise |last2=Mazetta |first2=Matthew |title=CORONAVIRUS/CECC imposes highest travel warning on all overseas destinations |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003200012 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Taiwanese authorities suspended tours to China starting in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Shu-fen |last2=Ko |first2=Lin |title=Taiwan to extend halt on all tours to China until end of February |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202001300017 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=30 January 2020}}</ref> The ban's duration was extended through April 2020,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Hsin-Yin |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan to extend suspension of tours to China until end of April |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002100023 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> and expanded to cover Hong Kong and Macau.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Shu-fen |last2=Chang |first2=Yi-ching |title=Taiwan halts all tours to Hong Kong, Macau |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002060014 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=6 February 2020}}</ref> Taiwan also announced a ban of cruise ships from entering all Taiwanese ports from January 6.<ref name=\"1TWCDC06Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/En/Bulletin/Detail/91k5k7M3AjnFGHnYsArIFw?typeid=158 |title=Central Epidemic Command Center (CECC) announces international cruise ships will be banned from calling at ports of Taiwan starting from February 6|date=6 February 2020 |website=Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)}}</ref> In January, Italy banned flights from Mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Hsin-Yin |title=CAL, EVA affected by Italy's suspension of Taiwan flights |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002010004 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Emerson |last2=Ku |first2=Chuan |title=Taiwan summons Italian representative over flight ban |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202002030011 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=3 February 2020}}</ref> However, [[China Airlines]] was permitted to fly Taiwanese nationals in Italy to Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Huang |first1=Ya-shih |last2=Wu |first2=Hsin-yun |last3=Huang |first3=Frances |last4=Lim |first4=Emerson |title=Italy allows CAL to fly Taiwanese passengers back to Taiwan |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202002010010 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wu |first1=Jui-chi |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=WUHAN VIRUS / Taiwan evacuates 169 on second flight from Hubei |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/cross-strait/202003110001 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 February, the Philippines announced a ban on the entry of Taiwanese citizens due to the [[One-China Policy]].<ref name=CNNPH10Feb2020>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/10/Taiwan-included-in-coronavirus-travel-ban.html|title= Taiwan included in coronavirus travel ban \u2013 DOH|date=10 February 2020|publisher=CNN|location=Philippines}}</ref> Later on 14 February, Presidential Spokesperson of Philippines, [[Salvador Panelo]], announced the lifting of the temporary ban on Taiwan.<ref name=CNNPH14Feb2020>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/14/Taiwan-travel-ban-lifted.html|title=Taiwan travel ban lifted \u2013 Palace|date=14 February 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref> On 23 February 2020, Taiwan banned frontline medical professionals working in hospitals from traveling to areas placed under a Level 3 travel alert.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Chen |first2=Yun-yu |last3=Yeh |first3=Joseph |title=Taiwan bans its healthcare professionals from traveling abroad |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002230009 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chen |first1=Wei-ting |last2=Chiang |first2=Yi-ching |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan amends travel ban on medical personnel |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002240006 |accessdate=26 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=24 February 2020}}</ref> The ban is to remain in place until 30 June.<ref name=taipeitimes2003731704>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=I-chia |title=Virus Outbreak: Med personnel travel ban until June 30 |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/27/2003731704 |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=27 February 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, the Executive Yuan announced that teachers and students at the secondary school level and below were prohibited from overseas travel until July.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hung-kuo |last2=Ko |first2=Lin |last3=Hsu |first3=Elizabeth |title=CORONAVIRUS / Students, teachers barred from overseas travel under Cabinet decision |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003160023 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Starting 19 March foreign nationals were barred from entering Taiwan, with some exceptions, such as those carrying out the term of a business contract, holding valid Alien Resident Certificates, diplomatic credentials, or other official documentation and special permits.<ref name=\"barentry\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 200px\"\n! Levels \n! Suggestions \n! Included countries/regions <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/CountryEpidLevel/Index/NlUwZUNvckRWQ09CbDJkRVFjaExjUT09|title=\u570b\u969b\u65c5\u904a\u75ab\u60c5\u5efa\u8b70\u7b49\u7d1a\u8868|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control (Taiwan)|Taiwan Centers for Disease Control]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EEEE00;| '''Level 1: Watch''' \n| style=\"background:#FFFFBB;| Follow local prevention measures<br>'''Self quarantine for 14 days''' required upon arrival\n| align=\"center\"| None\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF8800;| '''Level 2: Alert''' \n| style=\"background:#FFDDAA;| Further protective measures<br>'''Self quarantine for 14 days''' required upon arrival\n| align=\"center\"| None\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF0000;| '''Level 3: Warning''' \n| style=\"background:#FF8888;| Avoid all nonessential travels<br>'''Self quarantine for 14 days''' required upon arrival\n| align=\"center\"| Global\n|}\n\n==Economic impact==\n===Aviation===\nIn the aviation industry, Taiwanese carrier [[China Airlines]]'s direct flights to Rome have been rejected and cancelled since Italy has announced the ban on Taiwanese flights.<ref name=Reuters05Feb2020>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/china-health-taiwan-italy/italy-says-taiwan-flight-resumption-request-noted-after-virus-ban-idUSL4N2A52YR|title=Italy says Taiwan flight resumption request 'noted' after virus ban|date=5 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> The second-largest Taiwanese airline, [[Eva Air]], has also postponed the launch of [[Milan]] and [[Phuket]] flights.<ref name=FTW06Feb2020>{{cite news|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202002060022|title=EVA Air postpones new routes to Milan, Phuket due to epidemic|date=6 February 2020|agency=Central News Agency|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208142053/https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202002060022|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Both Taiwanese airlines have cut numerous [[Cross-Strait relations|cross-strait]] destinations, leaving just three Chinese cities still served.<ref name=TWaviation12Feb2020>{{cite web|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289492/china-taiwan-feb-apr-2020-cross-strait-service-changes-as-of-11feb20/|title= China / Taiwan Feb \u2013 Apr 2020 Cross-Strait service changes as of 11FEB20|date=12 February 2020|work=Routesonline}}</ref>\n\n===Stock markets===\n[[Taiwan Capitalization Weighted Stock Index]] has decreased over 13.1% due to the coronavirus. Foreign investors have sold over NT$200&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/taiwan-markets-outflows/taiwan-stocks-see-record-breaking-outflows-as-markets-tumble-idUSL4N2B52XN|title=Taiwan stocks see record-breaking outflows as markets tumble|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> TAIEX has also hit a 42-month low, closing at 8,681.34 points.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2020/03/20/2003733007|title=TAIEX hits 42-month low to close at 8,681.34 points|date=20 March 2020|work=Taipei Times}}</ref> National Stabilization Fund decided on 19 March that it is essential to intervene in the stock market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202003190026|title=Stabilization fund authorizes intervention in financial markets|date=19 March 2020|first1=Ku|last1=Chuan|first2=Matthew |last2=Mazetta|agency=Central News Agency}}</ref>\n\n==Evacuation related to the pandemic==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! style=\"width: 10%\" | Departure date\n! style=\"width: 10%;\" | Evacuees\n! style=\"width: 18%;\" | Departure airport\n! style=\"width: 18%;\" | Arrival airport\n! style=\"width: 55%;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|3 February 2020\n|{{Flagicon|TWN}} 247\n|[[Wuhan Tianhe International Airport]]\n|[[Taoyuan International Airport]]\n|Charter flight operated by [[China Eastern Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=16 March 2020|title=Taiwan's latest Wuhan virus patient was not listed for evacuation from China|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/cross-strait/202002050027|last1=Wang|first1=Yang-yu|last2=Miao|first2=Zhon-han|first3=Emerson |last3=Lim|agency=Central News Agency}}</ref>\n|-\n|21 February 2020\n|{{Flagicon|TWN}} 19\n|[[Haneda International Airport]]\n|[[Taoyuan International Airport]]\n|Evacuated Diamond Princess passengers.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Taiwan military disinfects plane carrying coronavirus ship evacuees|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/22/taiwan-military-disinfects-plane-carrying-coronavirus-ship-evacuees|date=22 February 2020|website=Euronews}}</ref>\n|-\n|2 March 2020\n|{{Flagicon|TWN}} 11\n|[[Istanbul Airport]]\n|[[Taoyuan International Airport]]\n|After an Israeli passenger on another Turkish Airlines flight tested positive, the airline ran a special flight to take a Taiwanese tour group on the same flight as the confirmed case home.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=17 March 2020|title=Taiwanese woman on same flight with COVID-19 patient hospitalized|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003020024|first2=Evelyn|last2=Kao|last1=Chen|first1=Wei-ting|agency=Central News Agency}}</ref>\n|-\n|10, 11 March 2020\n|{{Flagicon|TWN}} 361\n|[[Wuhan Tianhe International Airport]]\n|[[Taoyuan International Airport]]\n|After some conflict between the Chinese and Taiwanese governments, two flights, one operated by [[China Airlines]] with 169 evacuees and another by [[China Eastern Airlines]] carrying 192, arrived around 23:00 on 10 March and 4:00 on 11 March respectively.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=16 March 2020|title=Virus Outbreak: Flights bring 361 Taiwanese home|url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/03/12/2003732546|date=12 March 2020|work=Taipei Times|last1=Lee|first=I-chia}}</ref>\n|-\n|29, 30 March 2020\n|{{Flagicon|TWN}} 367\n|[[Shanghai Pudong International Airport]]\n|[[Taoyuan International Airport]]\n| A flight operated by China Airlines evacuated 153 Taiwanese nationals from Shanghai on 29 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Hung-kuo |last2=Wu |first2=Jui-chi |last3=Ko |first3=Lin |title=153 Taiwanese return from Hubei, placed in quarantine |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003300006 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> An additional 214 evacuees were flown to Taiwan on 30 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shen |first1=Peng-ta |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=214 Taiwanese back in Taiwan after long ordeal in Hubei province |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/cross-strait/202003300029 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 29 March 2020\n|{{Flagicon|TWN}} 55<br>{{Flagicon|JPN}} 29 <br>{{Flagicon|USA}} 34<br>{{Flagicon|SIN}} 14<br>{{Flagicon|MYS}} 7 \n|[[Alejandro Velasco Astete International Airport|Cusco International Airport]]<br />[[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport|Lima International Airport]]\n|[[Miami International Airport]]\n|The flight, chartered by [[LATAM Airlines]], departed from [[Cusco]], a southeastern city in [[Peru]], with 38 Taiwanese on board, then flew to the capital, [[Lima]], to pick up an additional 17 Taiwanese nationals. Another 84 passengers of four different nationalities\u2014Japan, Singapore, Malaysia, and the U.S.\u2013boarded the aircraft, bringing the total number of passengers to 139. The flight landed in Miami and all passengers were permitted to stay in the city or continue to their own country.<ref>{{cite work|first1=Matt|last2=Chiang|first2=Yi-ching|last1=Yu|accessdate=29 March 2020|date=29 March 2020|title=Second group of Taiwanese tourists in Peru take private charter to U.S.|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003290006|agency=Central News Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lu|first1=Yi-hsuan|accessdate=1 April 2020|date=30 March 2020|title=Virus Outbreak: Taiwan shares evacuation flight|url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/03/30/2003733650|work=Taipei Times}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==International responses==\nTaiwan's early deployment of epidemic control measures and follow-up actions have received international praise and approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/politics/breakingnews/3097286|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u300b\u53f0\u7063\u9632\u75ab\u570b\u969b\u80af\u5b9a\uff01\u8607\u63c6\uff1a\u56b4\u9632\u7b2c2\u6ce2\u75ab\u60c5\u56de\u6383 |trans-title = Wuhan Pneumonia \"Taiwan Epidemic Prevention International is sure! Su Shi: Prevent the second wave of epidemic review |date=12 March 2020|website=Liberty Times|accessdate=17 March 2020|language=zh}}</ref> On 13 March 2020, the Taiwanese [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] arranged for the Minister of Health, [[Chen Shih-chung]], to have a meeting with envoys and representatives from various countries, and the epidemic prevention methods were affirmed.<ref>[https://www.upmedia.mg/news_info.php?SerialNo=83202 \u53f0\u7063\u9632\u75ab\u53d7\u80af\u5b9a\u3000\u9673\u6642\u4e2d\uff1a\u5404\u570b\u4f7f\u7bc0\u99d0\u53f0\u4ee3\u8868\u90fd\u4f86\u4e86] \"Taiwan's epidemic prevention is confirmed\"\uff0c\u5468\u5e0c\u96ef\uff0c\u4e0a\u5831\u5feb\u8a0a</ref> Taiwan donated a total of 10 million masks with 7 million masks to Europe (Italy, Spain, Germany, France, Belgium, Netherland, Luxembourg, Czech, Poland, United Kingdom, Switzerland) and 2 million masks to United States, and 1 million to diplomatic allies on 1 April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sean Lin |title=Virus Outbreak: Taiwan joins global COVID-19 battle |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2020/04/02/2003733834 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |agency=The Taipei Times |publisher=The Taipei Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/taiwan-donate-10-million-masks-countries-hit-hardest/story?id=69918187|title=Taiwan to donate 10 million masks to countries hit hardest by coronavirus|date=2 April 2020|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company]]}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nThe [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC) pointed out several measures that Taiwan has taken to prevent community spread of the coronavirus. It emphasized that Taiwan has used lessons learned during the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]] to combat the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/taiwan-covid-19-lessons-1.5505031|title=Inside Taiwan during COVID-19: How the country kept schools and businesses open throughout pandemic|date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\nFormer [[Prime Minister of Denmark]], [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]], wrote an article for [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']], supporting Taiwanese participation within international organizations such as the [[World Health Organization]] in an effort to prevent deaths. He has compared preventative actions taken by the Taiwanese government and expressed the belief that other nations should have implemented such measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/|title= Taiwan Has Been Shut Out of Global Health Discussions. Its Participation Could Have Saved Lives|author=[[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]|date=18 March 2020|publisher=Time}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nGerman politician [[Sandra Bubendorfer-Licht]] described Taiwanese response to the virus as outstanding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/politics/breakingnews/3108832|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u300b\u53f0\u7063\u9632\u75ab\u63da\u540d\u5168\u7403\uff01 \u5fb7\u570b\u570b\u6703\u8b70\u54e1\uff1a\u722d\u53d6\u66f4\u591a\u5408\u4f5c |trans-title = Wuhan Pneumonia \"Taiwan epidemic prevention is famous all over the world! German parliamentarians: fight for more cooperation|date=22 March 2020|website=Liberty Times|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[Prime Minister of Israel|Israeli Prime Minister]] [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] indicated that the Israeli government would use Taiwan's experience to fight the epidemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/pm-says-all-leisure-venues-to-shut-urges-israel-to-adjust-to-new-way-of-life/|title=All leisure venues closing as Netanyahu tells Israel: Adjust to new way of life|work=The Times of Israel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-israel/israel-to-use-anti-terror-tech-to-counter-coronavirus-invisible-enemy-idUSKBN21113V|title=Israel to use anti-terror tech to counter coronavirus 'invisible enemy'|date=15 March 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===Japan===\nOn 10 March, the Japanese news site ''Foresight'' published an article by a freelance journalist named Nojima who is familiar with Taiwan affairs, analyzing Taiwan's policy decisions regarding the epidemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fsight.jp/articles/-/46630?st=%E5%8F%B0%E6%B9%BE|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u304b\u3089\u53f0\u6e7e\u3092\u5b88\u308b\u300c\u8521\u82f1\u6587\u653f\u6a29\u300d\u306e\u300c\u5f37\u529b\u5e03\u9663\u300d\u3068\u300c\u5927\u5c40\u5224\u65ad\u300d|date=10 March 2020|publisher=Foresight|lang=ja}}</ref> Japanese media also carried out long reports on [[Chen Shih-chung]], Tang Feng and others. Tang Feng received the most attention in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/article?a=20200316-00010003-nipponcom-soci|title= \u53f0\u6e7e\u306e\u300c\u5148\u624b\u9632\u75ab\u300d\u3068\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u300c\u30db\u30c8\u30b1\u9632\u75ab\u300d\u3001\u9055\u3044\u306f\u3069\u3053\u304b\u3089\u6765\u308b\u306e\u304b\uff1f|date=16 March 2020|publisher=Nippon.Com|lang=ja}}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\nDue to the influence of the Chinese (PRC) government, Taiwan has been excluded from the [[World Health Organization]]. <!-- The WHO asserts that it is in contact with the Taiwanese government on a technical level. Fake news, mostly from Chinese netizens rather than the Chinese government{{fact|date=March 2020}}, has become an issue. --> False reports of the outbreak spreading out of control in Southern Taiwan began in early January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled|title= With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled|date=13 March 2020|publisher=NPR|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nOn 15 March, Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] said New Zealand would follow Taiwan's example in their strategy to fight the epidemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120294477/coronavirus-new-zealand-likely-to-follow-taiwan-in-advising-cancellation-of-crowded-gatherings|title=Coronavirus: New Zealand likely to follow Taiwan in advising cancellation of crowded gatherings|publisher=Stuff|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> Several news outlets in New Zealand have also mentioned what Taiwan has done to prevent the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120449256/coronavirus-can-new-zealand-follow-taiwan-singapore-and-hong-kong-in-containing-the-spread|title= Coronavirus: Can New Zealand follow Taiwan, Singapore and Hong Kong in containing the spread?|date=21 March 2020|publisher=Stuff}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318687|title= Coronavirus: How New Zealand cases track against other countries at the same stage|date=21 March 2020|work=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref> TVNZ1 also reported Taiwan in the Saturday 6pm Headline. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/new-zealand-can-learn-other-countries-coronavirus-under-control|title=What New Zealand can learn from other countries where coronavirus is under control|date=4 April 2020|publisher=TVNZ1}}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\nDuring late February when South Korea was suffering from its domestic outbreak, the supplies of masks were running out. South Korean news started to emphasize Taiwan's masks policies, including ban on masks exports and masks selling policies, while criticizing the South Korean government for being too slow to react.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/202003060993798064|title='\ub9c8\uc2a4\ud06c 5\ubd80\uc81c \uc6d0\ubcf8' \ub300\ub9cc \ub9c8\uc2a4\ud06c \uc815\ucc45\uc740 \uc5b4\ub5bb\uac8c?|date=6 March 2020|work=The Korea Times|lang=korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/economy/view/2020/03/241469/|title=\ub9c8\uc2a4\ud06c \uc8fc 2\ub9e4\u00b7\uc694\uc77c\uc81c \ud310\ub9e4 `\ub300\ub9cc\ubaa8\ub378`\u2026\u97d3\ubcf4\ub2e4 \ud55c\ub2ec \ube68\ub790\ub2e4|date=8 March 2020|work=[[Maeil Business Newspaper]]|lang=korean}}</ref>\n\n===United States ===\nU.S. newspapers and magazines have suggested Taiwan and other Asian nations have done a better job at combating the coronavirus than the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/|title= What We Can Learn From Singapore, Taiwan and Hong Kong About Handling Coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/opinion/coronavirus-best-response.html|title=They've Contained the Coronavirus. Here's How.|date=13 March 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref> and mentioned how Taiwan has banned the export of masks and boosted mask production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/what-taiwan-can-teach-world-fighting-coronavirus-n1153826|title= What Taiwan can teach the world on fighting the coronavirus|date=10 March 2020|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n==International Status==\n===Dispute over political status===\n{{see also|China and the United Nations}}\n====International Civil Aviation Organization====\nThe [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO), a specialized civil aviation agency of the United Nations, rejected Taiwan's participation amid the novel coronavirus outbreak, which impacted Taiwan's ability to gather information from the international organization. In response to public inquiry on the organization's decision on Twitter, ICAO commented that their action is intended to \"defend the integrity of the information\".<ref name=axios919109887>{{cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/as-virus-spreads-un-agency-blocks-critics-taiwan-policy-on-twitter-e8a8bce6-f31a-4f41-89e0-77d919109887.html|title=UN aviation agency blocks critics of Taiwan policy on Twitter|author=Bethany Allen-Ebrahimian|date=27 January 2020}}</ref> The United Nations Secretary General described these inquiries as a misinformation campaign targeting ICAO.<ref name=20200128taiwanenglishnews>{{cite web|url=https://taiwanenglishnews.com/icao-blocks-debate-about-taiwans-exclusion-from-pandemic-prevention-efforts/|title=ICAO blocks debate about Taiwan's exclusion from pandemic-prevention efforts|author=Phillip Charlier|date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====World Health Organization====\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) have listed [[political status of Taiwan|Taiwan as part of China]], which resulted in multiple countries including Italy,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202002020005|title=Taiwan blasts WHO amid Italy's flight ban controversy|date=2 February 2020|agency=Central News Agency|last1=Lim|first1=Emerson}}</ref> Vietnam,<ref name=taiwannews3869705>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3869705|title=Vietnam lifts ban on Taiwan flights amid confusion stoked by WHO|date=3 February 2020|website=Taiwan News}}</ref> and the Philippines<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?unit=2&post=171504|title=MOFA welcomes Philippines' decision to lift Taiwan travel ban|date=15 February 2020|website=Taiwan Today}}</ref> briefly banning flights from Taiwan in January and February 2020, despite the disease not then having reached epidemic status in Taiwan.<ref name=20200203reuters>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/shut-out-of-who-taiwan-faces-flight-bans-update-delays-in-virus-crisis-idUSKBN1ZX0JK|title=Shut out of WHO, Taiwan faces flight bans, delays in virus updates|date=3 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=20200202reuters>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-scrambles-diplomats-to-keep-flights-going-amid-china-virus-inclusion-idUSKBN1ZW04H|title=Taiwan scrambles diplomats to keep flights going amid China virus inclusion|date=2 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n[[Johns Hopkins University]] Coronavirus Research Center hosted an interactive map which initially listed Taiwan under the category \"country/region\", along with Mainland China, Hong Kong, and Macau. On 10 March, Taiwan's name was switched to Taipei and environs, a designation used by the World Health Organization. When a news organization reached out, the associate professor in charge of the project claimed they would be changing it back to Taiwan immediately.<ref name=axios461906>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/johns-hopkins-coronavirus-map-taiwan-china-5c461906-4f1c-42e7-b78e-a4b43f4520ab.html|title=Johns Hopkins coronavirus map changes \"Taiwan\" to \"Taipei and environs\"|last=Allen-Ebrahimian|first=Bethany|website=Axios|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/|title=Johns Hopkins Coronavirus Resource Center|website=Johns Hopkins Coronavirus Resource Center|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> By 12 March, Taiwan was restored to the map, and the university stated that it would adhere to naming conventions developed by the [[United States Department of State]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chiang |first1=Chin-yeh |last2=Yeh |first2=Joseph |title=U.S. university revises reference to Taiwan on COVID-19 map |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202003120009 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Taiwan is excluded from the World Health Organization due to opposition from China, and thus has limited access to shared scientific information and data, the country's response has been lauded in international press.<ref name=businessinsider>{{Cite web |url= https://www.businessinsider.fr/us/coronavirus-taiwan-case-study-rapid-response-containment-2020-3?op=1 |title=Taiwan has only 50 coronavirus cases. Its response to the crisis shows that swift action and widespread healthcare can prevent an outbreak. |first=Isaac|last=Scher |date=13 March 2020 |website=Business Insider France}}</ref><ref name=USNews>{{cite web | title=Lessons Learned From Taiwan's Response to Coronavirus \u2013 Best Countries | website=US News & World Report | date=10 March 2020 | url= https://www.usnews.com/news/best-countries/articles/2020-03-10/lessons-learned-from-taiwans-response-to-coronavirus | access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=vox21171722>{{Cite web |url= https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2020/3/10/21171722/taiwan-coronavirus-china-social-distancing-quarantine |title=Taiwan has millions of visitors from China and only 45 coronavirus cases. Here's how. |first=Kelsey|last=Piper |date=10 March 2020 |website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=nbcnews1153826>{{Cite web |url= https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/what-taiwan-can-teach-world-fighting-coronavirus-n1153826 |title=What Taiwan can teach the world on fighting the coronavirus |publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Despite its proximity to China and large human flows, Taiwan has recorded the lowest incidence rate per capita \u2013 around 1 in every 500,000 people.<ref name=nbcnews1153826/> Success factors cited have included the fact that the country's vice president, [[Chen Chien-jen]], is an epidemiologist who had obtained a doctoral degree at the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health]];<ref name=USNews/> and the lessons learnt from the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS epidemic in 2003]], which hit Taiwan hard. Infrastructure, including the establishment of a national health command center integrating relevant agencies; data analytics; policies aimed at keeping healthcare affordable; and extensive educational outreach were put in place following the SARS outbreak.<ref name=businessinsider/><ref name=USNews/> Researchers at Stanford Health Policy researcher published an article in the ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' arguing that Taiwan's action plan \u2013 which included 124 discrete actions and coordination to be implemented in the first instance \u2013 including travel bans, quarantines, surveillance steps, social distancing \u2013 had saved Taiwan from a serious epidemic.<ref name=vox21171722/>\n\n===Cooporation with the United States===\n{{see also|Taiwan\u2013United States relations}}\n{{see also|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn 4 March, the [[U.S. House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] unanimously (415\u20130) passed a modified version of the [[TAIPEI Act]], with the goal of supporting Taiwan's attempts to join international organizations. On 11 March, the [[U.S. Senate|Senate]] unanimously passed the House's version of the TAIPEI Act.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202003120004|title=U.S. Senate passes TAIPEI Act unanimously|date=12 March 2020|agency=Central News Agency|first1=Stacy|last1=Hsu|last2=Ko|first2=Lin}}</ref> On 27 March, U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] signed the TAIPEI Act into law. The TAIPEI Act was denounced by the Chinese (PRC) government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-usa-idUSKBN21E0B7|title=U.S. increases support for Taiwan in recognition battle with China|date=27 March 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> \n\nOn 18 March, the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that the United States would cooperate with Taiwan on researching and developing vaccines and rapid tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003180010|title= Taiwan, U.S. announce joint efforts to fight coronavirus|date=18 March 2020|agency=Central News Agency|first1=Emerson|last1=Lim}}</ref> The United States and Taiwan held an online forum \nwhich focused on the participation of Taiwan in the World Health Organization and how to share the success that Taiwan has done throughout the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-usa/taiwan-talks-who-role-with-u-s-china-denounces-manipulation-idUSKBN21L12V|title=Taiwan talks WHO role with U.S., China denounces 'manipulation'|date=3 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> [[Chinese Foreign Ministry]] spokesperson [[Hua Chunying]] criticized the U.S. and Taiwanese government of such action as political manipulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/04/03/taiwan-talks-who-role-with-us-china-denounces-manipulation.html|title=Taiwan talks WHO role with US, China denounces 'manipulation'|date=3 April 2020|publisher=The Jakarta Post}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Face mask control measures===\n[[File:04.02 \u7e3d\u7d71\u8996\u5bdf\u300c\u4e2d\u592e\u6d41\u884c\u75ab\u60c5\u6307\u63ee\u4e2d\u5fc3\u300d 49726568957 66543b616e o.jpg|thumb|President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] wearing a mask]]\nThe Taiwanese government announced the ban on the export of face masks before the epidemic had spread to many countries, which caused controversy; however, after the outbreak of the epidemic, people rushed to buy masks in many countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5785223/medical-masks-coronavirus-covid-19/|title= There Aren't Enough Medical Masks to Fight Coronavirus. Here's Why It's Not Going to Get Better Anytime Soon|work=Time|date=27 February 2020}}</ref> Incidents of face mask confiscation by the government also occurred in mainland China, the world's top face mask manufacturer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/business/masks-china-coronavirus.html|title= The World Needs Masks. China Makes Them \u2013 But Has Been Hoarding Them. |date=13 March 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/zh-tw/news/world/%E6%AD%A6%E6%BC%A2%E8%82%BA%E7%82%8E%E7%87%92%E5%87%BA%E4%BA%82%E4%B8%96%EF%BC%81%E9%99%B8%E5%90%84%E7%9C%81%E3%80%8C%E4%BA%92%E6%89%A3%E3%80%8D%E5%8F%A3%E7%BD%A9%E5%8F%8A%E7%89%A9%E8%B3%87-%E7%B5%90%E5%B1%80%E6%9B%9D%E5%85%89/ar-BBZIBMI|title=\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u71d2\u51fa\u4e82\u4e16\uff01\u9678\u5404\u7701\u300c\u4e92\u6263\u300d\u53e3\u7f69\u53ca\u7269\u8cc7 \u7d50\u5c40\u66dd\u5149|publisher=\u4eca\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn early February 2020, the [[Executive Yuan]] adopted the recommendations of professors Huang Li-min (\u9ec3\u7acb\u6c11) and Chang Shang-chwen (\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3) of the [[National Taiwan University]] Medical School, advocating that healthy people do not need to wear masks in open spaces. On 8 February, Chen Shih-chung, commander of the Central Epidemic Prevention Center, further stated that there was no need to wear a mask on public transportation.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u9673\u6642\u4e2d\uff1a\u53e3\u7f69\u642d\u5927\u773e\u904b\u8f38\u5de5\u5177\u514d\u6234 \u642d\u98db\u6a5f\u4e00\u5b9a\u8981\u6234|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002070330.aspx |language=zh}}</ref> This caused a storm of protest. The main point of contention is that public transportation such as buses and MRT carriages are confined spaces, and viruses are transmitted more easily than in open spaces.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u642d\u6377\u904b\u8981\u6234\u53e3\u7f69\uff1f\u885b\u798f\u90e8\u7d66\u51fa\u7b54\u6848\u3000\u5168\u5834\u8b41\u7136\uff1a\u96e3\u4ee5\u7f6e\u4fe1\u554a |url=https://today.line.me/tw/pc/article/%E6%90%AD%E6%8D%B7%E9%81%8B%E8%A6%81%E6%88%B4%E5%8F%A3%E7%BD%A9%EF%BC%9F%E8%A1%9B%E7%A6%8F%E9%83%A8%E7%B5%A6%E5%87%BA%E7%AD%94%E6%A1%88%E3%80%80%E5%85%A8%E5%A0%B4%E8%AD%81%E7%84%B6%EF%BC%9A%E9%9B%A3%E4%BB%A5%E7%BD%AE%E4%BF%A1%E5%95%8A-gvgK9N |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn early April, Taiwan President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] announced to donate 10 million masks to countries that suffered severely from the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-economy/taiwan-to-spend-35-billion-fighting-virus-to-donate-10-million-masks-idUSKBN21J41C|title=Taiwan to spend $35 billion fighting virus, to donate 10 million masks|date=1 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> In response to the donation, [[European Commission]] President [[Ursula von der Leyen]] wrote in a tweet that the European Union \"really appreciate[d] this gesture of solidarity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3078032/eu-leader-ursula-von-der-leyen-risks-beijings-ire-lauding|title=EU leader Ursula von der Leyen risks Beijing\u2019s ire by lauding Taiwan\u2019s donation of 5.6 million masks for coronavirus battle|date=2 April 2020|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref> U.S. [[National Security Council]] also wrote a tweet thanking Taiwan to \"support and collaborate\" with the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/politics/202004030004|title=U.S. National Security Council thanks Taiwan for pledged mask donations|date=3 April 2020|publisher=Focus Taiwan}}</ref> In a press conference on April 1, [[Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] spokesperson [[Hua Chunying]] responded to questions about the mask donations advising anyone in Taiwan who would seek to politicize the pandemic to \"think twice and act prudently\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/taiwan-to-donate-2m-hospital-masks-to-united-states|title=Taiwan to donate 2M hospital masks to United States|date=1 April 2020|publisher=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{notelist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Taiwan|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Taiwan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Taiwan]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Kingnosis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCases:Updating numbers for Apr 5", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Taiwan"}
{"title_page": "Ragnar Lodbrok", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Harley MS 2278, folio 39r excerpt.jpg|thumb|Lothbrocus and his sons [[Ivar the Boneless|Ivar]] and [[Ubba]]. 15th-century miniature in ''[[Harleian Library|Harley]] MS 2278'', folio 39r.]]\n'''Ragnar Lodbrok''' or '''Lothbrok''' ({{lang-non|Ragnarr Lo\u00f0br\u00f3k}}, \"Ragnar shaggy breeches\", [[Modern Icelandic]]: ''Ragnar Lo\u00f0br\u00f3k'') in [[saga]]s  is a historically dubious{{sfn|Magnusson|2008|p=106}} legendary {{sfn|Harrison|1993|p=16}} [[Norsemen|Norse]] [[Viking]] hero, as well as Danish and Swedish King, known from [[Viking Age]] [[Old Norse poetry]], Icelandic stories, and near contemporary chronicles. According to the traditional literature, Ragnar Lodbrok distinguished himself by many raids against the [[British Isles]] and [[Holy Roman Empire]] during the 9th century. According to the sagas Ragnar Lodbrok's father was the [[Legendary Kings of Sweden|legendary Swedish king]] [[Sigurd Ring]]. <ref>https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/Ragnar-Lothbrok/</ref>\n\n== Accounts ==\n=== The Icelandic Sagas ===\nAccording to the ''[[Saga of Ragnar Lodbrok]]'', ''[[Tale of Ragnar's sons]]'', ''[[Heimskringla]]'', ''[[Hervarar Saga]]'', ''[[S\u00f6gubrot]]'', and many other Icelandic sources, Ragnar was the son of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] king [[Sigurd Ring]]. Nearly all of the sagas agree that [[Randver]] was Sigurd's father, with the ''[[Hervarar saga]]'' citing his wife as \u00c5sa, the daughter of King [[Harald Granraude|Harald of the Red Moustache]] from Norway. The accounts further tell that Randver was a grandson of the legendary Scandinavian king [[Ivar Vidfamne]] by his daughter Aud (whom the ''[[Hervarar saga]]'' calls Alfhild).<ref>Tolkien, Christopher, & Turville-Petre, G. (eds) (1956) ''Hervarar Saga ok Heidreks''. London: Viking Society for Northern Research, p. 68-9. [http://www.vsnrweb-publications.org.uk/Text%20Series/Hervarar%20saga%20ok%20heidreks.pdf]\n</ref> After the death of king [[Ivar Vidfamne]], Aud's eldest son by the [[Danes|Danish]] king [[Hr\u0153rekr Ringslinger]], Harald, conquered all of his grandfather's territory and became known as [[Harald Wartooth]]. Harald's nephew [[Sigurd Ring]] became the chief king of Sweden after Randver's death (Denmark according to ''Hervarar saga''), presumably as the subking of Harald. Sigurd and Harald fought the Battle of the Br\u00e1vellir ([[Br\u00e5valla]]) on the plains of [[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]], where Harald and many of his men died. Sigurd then ruled Sweden and Denmark (being sometimes identified with a Danish king [[Sigfred]] who ruled from about 770 until his death prior to 804). He sired a son with the Norwegian princess Alfhild of the semi-mythical \u00c1lfar people, Ragnar Lodbrok, who succeeded him.<ref>''S\u00f6gubrot'', Chapter 10 [https://web.archive.org/web/20100908081803/http://www.oe.eclipse.co.uk/nom/Fragment.htm]</ref> [[Eysteinn Beli]], who according to the ''[[Hervarar Saga]]'' was Harald Wartooth's son, ruled Sweden sometime after Sigurd until he was slain by the sons of Ragnar and [[Aslaug]].<ref>''The Tale of Ragnar's Sons'', Chapter 2 [http://www.germanicmythology.com/FORNALDARSAGAS/ThattrRagnarsSonar.html]</ref> \n\nIn their accounts of his reign, the Icelandic sagas tell more about Ragnar's marriages than about feats of warfare. According to the ''[[Sogubrot|S\u00f6gubrot]]'', \"he was the biggest and fairest of men that human eyes have seen, and he was like his mother in appearance and took after her kin\".<ref>''S\u00f6gubrot'', Chapter 10 [[https://web.archive.org/web/20100908081803/http://www.oe.eclipse.co.uk/nom/Fragment.htm]</ref> He first killed a giant snake that guarded the abode of the [[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland|East Geatic]] jarl's daughter [[Thora Borgarhjort]], thereby winning her as his wife. The unusual protective clothes that Ragnar wore, when attacking the serpent, earned him the nickname Lodbrok (\"shaggy breeches\"). His sons with Thora were [[Erik Weatherhat|Erik]] and Agnar. After Thora died, he discovered [[Aslaug|Kr\u00e1ka]], a woman of outstanding beauty and wisdom living with a poor peasant couple in [[Norway]], and married her. This marriage resulted in the sons [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], [[Hvitserk]], Ragnvald and [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]].<ref>''Ragnars Saga Lodbrokar'', Chapters 4 and 7 [https://www.snerpa.is/net/forn/ragnar.htm]</ref> Kr\u00e1ka was later revealed to actually be [[Aslaug]], a secret daughter of the renowned hero [[Sigurd|Sigurd Fafnesbane]]. As the sons grew up to become renowned warriors, Ragnar, not wishing to be outdone, resolved to conquer [[England]] with merely two ships. He was however defeated by superior English forces and was thrown into a snake pit to die in agony.<ref>''Ragnars Saga Lodbrokar'', Chapter 15 [https://www.snerpa.is/net/forn/ragnar.htm]</ref> The ''[[Saga of Ragnar Lodbrok]]'', ''[[Tale of Ragnar's Sons]]'', and ''[[Heimskringla]]'' all tell of the [[Great Heathen Army]] that invaded England at around 866, led by the sons of Ragnar Lodbrok to wreak revenge against King [[\u00c6lla of Northumbria]] who is told to have captured and executed Ragnar.\n\n=== Danish sources ===\nThe ''[[Chronicon Roskildense]]'' (c. 1138) mentions Lodbrok (Lothpardus) as father to the utterly cruel Norse King Ywar (rex crudelissimus Normannorum Ywar) and his brothers, Inguar (a double of Ywar), Ubbi, Byorn and Ulf, who rule the northern peoples. They call on the various Danish petty kings to help them ruin the realm of the [[Franks]]. Ywar successfully attacks the kingdoms of [[Great Britain|Britain]], though not as an act of revenge as in the Icelandic sagas.<ref>''Chronicon Roskildense'', p. 16[https://archive.org/stream/scriptoresminore112gert#page/16/mode/2up]</ref> The chronicle of [[Sven Aggesen]] (c. 1190) is the first Danish text that mentions the full name, Regnerus Lothbrogh. His son Sigurd invades Denmark and kills its king, whose daughter he marries as he takes over the throne. Their son in turn is [[Hardeknud I|Knut]], ancestor of the later Danish kings.<ref>Sven Aggeson, p. 106[https://archive.org/stream/scriptoresminore112gert#page/106/mode/2up]</ref> \n\nNeither of these sources mentions Ragnar Lodbrok as a Danish ruler. The first to do so is [[Saxo Grammaticus]] in his work ''[[Gesta Danorum]]'' (c. 1200). This work mixes Norse legend with data about Danish history derived from the chronicle of [[Adam of Bremen]] (c. 1075).<ref>Storm (1877), p. 387-9 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639&view=1up&seq=399] </ref> Here Ragnar's father Sigurd Ring is a Norwegian prince married to a Danish princess, and different from the victor of Br\u00e1vellir (who had flourished about thirteen generations earlier). Sigurd Ring and his cousin and rival Ring (that is, [[Sigfred (Danish king 812)|Sigfred]] and [[Anulo]] of recorded history, d. 812) are both killed in battle, whereupon Ragnar is elevated to the Danish kingship (identified by Saxo with [[Reginfrid|Ragnfred]], d. 814<ref>Storm (1877), p. 399 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639&view=1up&seq=411]</ref>).<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 539-41 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/541]</ref>  His first deed is the defeat of the Swedish king Fr\u00f6, who has killed Ragnar's grandfather. Ragnar is assisted in this by the ferocious shield-maiden [[Ladgerda]], whom he forces to marry him. In this marriage he sires the son Fridleif and two daughters.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 542-3 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/543]</ref>  He later repudiates the unreliable Ladgerda and instead wins the daughter of the Swedish king [[Herrau\u00f0r]], [[Thora Borgarhjort|Thora]], after killing two venomous giant snakes that guard her residence. His sons with Thora are Radbard, Dunvat, [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], Agnar and [[Ivar the Boneless]]. From a non-marital affair with the daughter of one Esbj\u00f8rn, Ragnar begets [[Ubba|Ubbe]], while his last marriage with Svanlaug produces another three sons, Ragnvald, [[Eric Weatherhat]] and [[Hvitserk]].<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 545, 550 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/550]</ref> \n\nThe sons were installed as sub-kings in various conquered territories. Ragnar led a Viking expedition to England and slew its king Hama, proceeding to kill the earls of [[Scotland]] and install Sigurd Snake-in-the Eye and Radbard as governors. Norway was also subjugated, and Fridleif was made ruler there and in [[Orkney]]. Later on, Ragnar with three sons invaded Sweden where a new king called S\u00f6rle had appeared and withheld the heritage of Thora's sons. S\u00f6rle and his army were massacred and Bj\u00f6rn Ironside was installed on the throne.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 551 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/551]</ref>  Some time later Bj\u00f6rn was put in charge of Norway, while Ragnar appointed another son, Eric Weatherhat, as ruler in Sweden; he was subsequently killed by a certain [[Eysteinn Beli|Eysteinn]]. One of the sons, Ubbe, revolted against his father at the instigation of his maternal grandfather Esbj\u00f8rn, and could only be defeated and captured with utmost effort.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 557 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/557]</ref> Saxo moreover tells of repeated expeditions to the [[British Isles]], one of which cost the lives of Dunvat and Radbard. \u00c6lla, son of Hama, expelled Ragnar's sub-ruler Ivar the Boneless from England with the help of the Galli (Gaill, Hiberno-Norse?<ref>Smyth (1977).</ref>) and remained a persistent enemy.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 560-1 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/560]</ref> Finally, the [[Scythians]] were forced to accept Hvitserk as their ruler. In the end Hvitserk was treacherously captured by the [[Hellespontus (province)|Hellespontian]] prince Daxon and burnt alive with his own admission. Hearing this, Ragnar led an expedition to [[Kievan Rus']] and captured Daxon who was curiously spared and exiled.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 558-9 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/558]</ref> \n\nUnlike the Icelandic sources, Saxo's account of Ragnar Lodbrok's reign is largely a catalog of successful Viking invasions over an enormous geographical area. Among the seaborne expeditions was one against the [[Bjarmians]] and [[Finns]] ([[Sami people|Saami]]) in the Arctic north. The Bjarmian use of magic spells caused foul weather and the sudden death of many Danish invaders, and the Finnish archers on skis turned out to be a formidable foe. Eventually these two tribes were put to flight and the Bjarmian king was slain.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 558-9 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/554]</ref> The historical king [[Harald Klak]] is by Saxo (based on a passage in Adam's chronicle) made into another persistent enemy of Ragnar, who several times incited the [[Jutes]] and [[Sk\u00e5ne|Scanians]] to rebel, but was regularly defeated. After the last victory over Harald, Ragnar learned that King \u00c6lla had massacred Ragnar's men on [[Ireland]]. Incensed, he attacked the English king with his fleet but was captured and thrown into the snake pit, similar to the Icelandic sagas. In spite of all his praise for Ragnar Lodbrok, Saxo also considers his fate as God's rightful vengeance for the contempt he had shown the Christian religion.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 562-3 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/563]</ref>\n\n=== Poetic and epigraphic sources ===\nWhile the narrative Norse sources date from the 12th and 13th centuries, there are also many older poems that mention him and his kin. The ''[[Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa]]'', ostensibly composed by [[Bragi Boddason]] in the 9th century, praises a Ragnar, son of Sigurd, for a richly decorated shield that the poet has received. The shield depicts the assault on [[Ermanaric|J\u00f6rmunrek]], the [[Hja\u00f0ningav\u00edg]] tale, the ploughing of [[Gefjon]], and [[Thor]]'s struggle with the [[Midgard Serpent]]. Recent scholarship has suggested that the poem is in fact from c. 1000 and celebrates the Norse reconquest of England. The four tales depicted on the shield would then symbolize four aspects of the Lodbrok saga (the initial defeat of the sons of Lodbrok in England due to recklessness, Ivar the Boneless's deceitful approach to King \u00c6lla, Ivar's cunning snatching of land from \u00c6lla, Ragnar's struggle against the giant serpent in order to win Thora).<ref>\"Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa\", ''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 24, p. 115.</ref> The ''Knutsdrapa'' of [[Sigvat Thordarson]] (c. 1038) mentions the death of \u00c6lla at the hands of Ivar in [[York]], who \"carved the eagle on \u00c6lla's back\".<ref>Smyth (1977), p. 193-4.</ref> From this the story of the atrocious revenge of Lodbrok's sons already seems to be present. The reference to a \"[[blood eagle]]\" punishment has however been much debated by modern scholars.<ref>[[Rory McTurk]], \"Kings and kingship in Viking Northumbria\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20080926171200/http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm]</ref> Another lay, ''[[Krakumal]]'', put in the mouth of the dying Ragnar in the snake pit, recounts the exploits of Ragnar and mentions battles over a wide geographical area, several relating to the British isles. The poem's name, \"Kr\u00e1ka's lay\", alludes to Ragnar's wife's [[Aslaug|Kr\u00e1ka]],<ref>\"Kr\u00e1kum\u00e1l\", ''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 17 (2001), p. 299-300.</ref> though modern philologists commonly date it to the 12th century in its present form.<ref>Smyth (1977), p. 73-80.</ref> \n\nThere is one runic inscription mentioning Lodbrok, carved on the prehistorical tumulus of [[Maeshowe]] on [[Orkney]] in the early 12th century. It reads: \"This howe was built a long time before Lodbrok's. Her sons, they were bold; scarcely ever were there such tall men of their hands\".<ref>Smyth (1977), p. 81.</ref> The expression \"her sons\" has given rise to the theory that Lodbrok was originally thought of as a woman,<ref>Gustav Storm (1877), \"Ragnar Lodbrok og Lodbrokss\u00f8nnerne; studie i dansk oldhistorie og nordisk sagnhistorie\", ''Historisk Tidskrift'' II:1 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639;view=1up;seq=419]</ref> mother of the historically known sons.<ref>[[Rory McTurk]], \"Kings and kingship in Viking Northumbria\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20080926171200/http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm]; </ref>\n\n=== Frankish accounts of a 9th-century Viking leader named Ragnar ===\nThe [[Siege of Paris (845)|Siege of Paris]] and the Sack of Paris of 845 was the culmination of a Viking invasion of the kingdom of the [[West Francia|West Franks]]. The Viking forces were led by a Norse chieftain named \"Reginherus\", or Ragnar.{{Sfn | Kohn | 2006 | p = 588}}  This Ragnar has often been tentatively identified with the legendary saga figure Ragnar Lodbrok,<ref>''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 24, p. 111, 113, 116.</ref> but the accuracy of this is disputed by historians.{{Sfn | Jones | 2001 | p = 212}}{{Sfn | Sprague | 2007 | p = 225}} Ragnar Lodbrok is also sometimes identified with a Ragnar who was awarded land in [[Torhout]], [[Flanders]], by [[Charles the Bald]] in about 841 but eventually lost the land as well as the favour of the King.{{Sfn | Sawyer | 2001 | p = 40}}  Ragnar's Vikings raided [[Rouen]] on their way up the Seine in 845  and in response to the invasion, determined not to let the royal [[Basilica of St Denis|Abbey of Saint-Denis]] (near Paris) be destroyed, Charles assembled an army which he divided into two parts, one for each side of the river.{{Sfn | Duckett | 1988 | p = 181}}{{Sfn | Jones | 2001 |  p = 212}} Ragnar attacked and defeated one of the divisions of the smaller Frankish army, took 111 of their men as prisoners and hanged them on an island on the Seine to honour the [[Norse religion|Norse god]] [[Odin]], as well as to incite terror in the remaining Frankish forces.{{Sfn | Kohn | 2006 | p = 588}}{{Sfn | Jones | 2001 | p = 212}} Ragnar's fleet made it back to his overlord, the Danish King [[Horik I]], but Ragnar soon died from a violent illness that also spread in Denmark.<ref>Storm (1877), p. 438 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639&view=1up&seq=450]</ref>\n\n=== Later continental accounts ===\nAmong the oldest texts to mention the name Lodbrok is the Norman history of [[William of Jumi\u00e8ges]] from c. 1070. According to William, the Danish kings of old had the custom to expel the younger sons from the kingdom to have them out of the way. At a time it happened that King [[Ragnar Lodbrok|Lodbrok]] succeeded his unnamed father on the Danish throne. After gaining power he honoured the said custom and ordered his junior son [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]] to leave his realm. Bj\u00f6rn thus left Denmark with a considerable fleet and started to ravage in [[West Francia]] and later the [[Mediterranean]].<ref>Guillaume de Jumi\u00e8ges, ''Histoire des ducs de Normandie'', p. 11-3 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015013753564;view=1up;seq=23]</ref> Roughly contemporary with William is [[Adam of Bremen]] whose history of the [[Archbishopric of Hamburg|Archbishopric of Hamburg-Bremen]] contains many traditions about Viking Age Scandinavia. In a passage referring to the Viking raids of the late 9th century, he mentions the Danish or Norse pirates Horich, Orwig, Gotafrid, Rudolf and Inguar (Ivar). This Ivar is in particular seen as a cruel persecutor of Christians, and a son of Lodbrok (Inguar, filius Lodparchi).<ref>Adam von Bremen, ''Hamburgische Kirchengeschichte'', p. 39-40[https://archive.org/stream/adamvonbremenham00adam#page/40/mode/2up]</ref>\n\n=== Anglo-Saxon and Irish accounts of the father of Ivar and Halfdan ===\nAccording to the contemporary ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' and [[Asser]]'s ''Life of Alfred'', in 878 the \"brother of Hingwar and Healfden\", with a naval fleet, a contingent of the [[Great Heathen Army]] invaded [[Devon]] in England and fought the [[Battle of Cynwit]]. There the Vikings lost, their king slain and many dead, with few escaping to their ships. After the battle the [[Saxons]] took great plunder, and among other things the banner called \"Raven\".<ref>Garmonsway, G.N. (1972), ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''. London: Dent, p. 75-7.</ref> The early 12th century ''[[Annals of St Neots]]'' further state that ''\"they say that the three sisters of Hingwar and Hubba, daughters of Lodebroch (Lodbrok), wove that flag and got it ready in one day. They say, moreover, that in every battle, wherever the flag went before them, if they were to gain the victory a live crow would appear flying on the middle of the flag; but if they were doomed to be defeated it would hang down motionless, and this was often proved to be so.\"''<ref>Garmonsway, G.N. (1972), ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''. London: Dent, p. 77.</ref>\nThis is among the earlier references to the legendary hero Ragnar Lodbrok.\n\nThe Irish ''[[Cogad G\u00e1edel re Gallaib]]'' from the 12th century, with information deriving from earlier annals, mentions king Halfdan (d. 877) under the name \"mac Ragnaill\".<ref>James Todd (1867), ''Cogadh Gaedhel re Gallaibh'', London: Longman, p. 27 [https://archive.org/details/cogadhgaedhelreg00todd/page/26/mode/2up]</ref> The form Ragnall may refer to either Ragnvald or Ragnar, and the entry is a strong indication that the name of Ivar's and Halfdan's father was really Ragnar or a similar name.<ref>Smyth, Alfred P. (1977) ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, p. 263, 279.</ref> The early 11th century ''[[Three Fragments]]'' contains a passage that gives a semi-legendary background to the capture of York by the Vikings in 866. The two younger sons of Halfdan, King of [[Lochlann]], expelled the eldest son Ragnall who sailed to the [[Orkney islands]] with his three sons and settled there. Two of the sons later raided the English and [[Franks]], proceeding to plunder in the Mediterranean. One of them learnt from a vision that Ragnall had fought a battle where the third son had been slain and in which he himself had most likely perished. The two Viking sons then returned home with a lot of dark-skinned captives.<ref>Smyth, Alfred P. (1977) ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, p. 62.</ref> It has been hypothesized that this is an Irish version of ''[[Ragnar Lodbrok's saga]]'', the Mediterranean expedition being a historical event taking place in 859-61.<ref>Smyth, Alfred P. (1977) ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, p. 64-5.</ref>\n\n== Ragnar's sons ==\n[[File:Rayner Lothbroc Saga by Norstedts 1880.jpg|thumb|upright|The saga as published by [[Norstedts]] in a large-size illustrated version (1880).]]\nThe [[Great Heathen Army]] is said to have been led by the sons of Ragnar Lodbrok, to wreak revenge against King [[\u00c6lla of Northumbria]] who had previously executed Ragnar by casting him into a pit full of venomous snakes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ancient-origins.net/history-famous-people/ragnar-lothbrok-ferocious-viking-hero-became-myth-008177|title=Ragnar Lothbrok: The Ferocious Viking Hero that Became a Myth|last=Karasavvas|first=Theodoros|work=Ancient Origins|access-date=28 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> Among the organizers were at least some of the brothers [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Ubba]], [[Halfdan Ragnarsson|Halfdan]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], [[Hvitserk]], and [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]], all of which are known as historical figures, save the slightly more dubious [[Hvitserk]].{{sfn|Holman|2003|p=220}} Ivar the Boneless was the leader of the Great Heathen Army from 865 to 870, but he disappears from English historical accounts after 870.<ref> Forte, Angelo; Oram, Richard; Pedersen, Frederik (30 May 2005). Viking Empires (First ed.). Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9780521829922}}</ref> The Anglo-Saxon chronicler [[\u00c6thelweard (historian)|\u00c6thelweard]] records Ivar's death as 870.<ref>Giles, J. A., ed. (10 September 2010). Six Old English Chronicles: Ethelwerd's Chronicle, Asser's Life Of Alfred, Geoffrey Of Monmouth's British History, Gildas, Nennius And Richard Of Cirencester. Kessinger Publishing, LLC. {{ISBN|9781163125991}}</ref> [[Halfdan Ragnarsson]] became the leader of the Great Heathen Army in about 870 and he led it in an invasion of Wessex.<ref>Forte, A; Oram, RD; Pedersen, F (2005). Viking Empires. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-82992-2}}. p. 72</ref> A great number of Viking warriors arrived from Scandinavia, as part of the Great Summer Army, led by King [[Bagsecg]] of Denmark, bolstering the ranks of Halfdan's army.<ref>Hooper, Nicholas Hooper; Bennett, Matthew (1996). The Cambridge Illustrated Atlas of Warfare: the Middle Ages. Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-44049-1}}. p.22</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'', the Danes battled the West Saxons nine times, including the [[Battle of Ashdown]] on 8 January 871, where Bagsecg was killed.<ref>Costambeys, M (2004). \"H\u00e1lfdan (d. 877)\". Oxford Dictionary of National Biography. Oxford University Press. {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/49260}}</ref> Halfdan accepted a truce from the future [[Alfred the Great]], newly crowned king of Wessex.<ref>Forte, A; Oram, RD; Pedersen, F (2005). Viking Empires. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-82992-2}}. pp. 72\u201373</ref> After Bagsecg's death Halfdan was the only remaining king of the invading host. He may also have been a King of part of Denmark ([[Jutland]]?), since a co-ruler [[Sigfred and Halfdan|Halfdan]] is mentioned in Frankish sources in 873.<ref>''Die Jahrb\u00fccher von Fulda und Xanten'', p. 62 [https://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb10015821_00076.html]</ref> According to late sagas Bj\u00f6rn Ironside became King of Sweden and Uppsala, although this presents chronological inconsistencies.<ref>Carl Bernadotte et al. (1956), ''Sveriges hundra konungar''. Stockholm: Biblioteksb\u00f6cker, p. 81. </ref> Bj\u00f6rn had two sons, [[Erik Bj\u00f6rnsson|Erik]] and [[Refil Bj\u00f6rnsson]]. His son Erik became the next king of Sweden, and was succeeded in turn by [[Erik Refilsson]], the son of Refil.<ref>Tolkien, Christopher, & Turville-Petre, G. (eds) (1956) ''Hervarar Saga ok Heidreks''. London: Viking Society for Northern Research, p. 69. [http://www.vsnrweb-publications.org.uk/Text%20Series/Hervarar%20saga%20ok%20heidreks.pdf]\n</ref> Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye is perhaps the same person as [[Sigfred and Halfdan|Sigfred]], brother of Halfdan, who was king in Denmark together with Halfdan in 873.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm ''Kings and kingship in Viking Northumbria'', by [[Rory McTurk]] (University of Leeds)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926171200/http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm |date=26 September 2008 }}</ref> According to the sagas Sigurd became King of [[Zealand]], [[Sk\u00e5ne]] and the lesser Danish Isles.<ref>''The Tale of Ragnar's Sons'', Chapter 3 [http://www.germanicmythology.com/FORNALDARSAGAS/ThattrRagnarsSonar.html]</ref> Sigfred-Sigurd possibly succeeded his brother Halfdan as King of entire Denmark in about 877, and may be the Viking king Sigfred who was killed in [[West Francia]] in 887.<ref>P.A. Munch (1852), ''Det norske Folks Historie'', Vol. I:1. Christiania: Tonsberg, p. 642-8.</ref>\n\n== Sources and historical accuracy ==\n[[File:Rayner Lothbroc & Kraka by August Malmstr\u00f6m c 1880.jpg|upright|thumb|Ragnar receives [[Aslaug|Kr\u00e1ka]] (Aslaug), as imagined by [[August Malmstr\u00f6m]].]]\n[[File:Ragnar Lodbroks d\u00f6d by Hugo Hamilton.jpg|thumb|right|19th-century artist's impression of \u00c6lla of Northumbria's execution of Ragnar Lodbrok]]\nWhereas Ragnar's sons [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Halfdan Ragnarsson]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], [[Ubba|Ubbe]] and [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]] are historical figures, opinion regarding their father is divided. Modern academia regards most of the stories about him to be fiction. According to [[Hilda Ellis Davidson]], writing in 1979,\n\n<blockquote>Certain scholars in recent years have come to accept at least part of Ragnar's story as based on historical fact.<ref>Davidson p. 277</ref></blockquote> A generation later, however, Katherine Holman wrote in 2003: <blockquote>Although his sons are historical figures, there is no evidence that Ragnar himself ever lived and he seems to be an amalgam of historical figures and literary invention.<ref name=\"Z\">Holman 2003 p. 220</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe most significant medieval sources that mention Ragnar include:\n* Book IX of the ''[[Gesta Danorum]]'', a 12th-century work by the Christian Danish chronicler [[Saxo Grammaticus]]\n* the ''[[Tale of Ragnar's Sons|Tale of Ragnar's sons]]'' (''Ragnarssona \u00fe\u00e1ttr''), a [[legendary saga]]\n* the ''[[Tale of Ragnar Lothbrok ]]'', another saga, a sequel to the ''[[V\u00f6lsunga saga]]''\n* the ''[[Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa]]'', a [[skaldic poem]] of which only fragments remain, attributed to the 9th-century poet [[Bragi Boddason]]\n* the ''[[Kr\u00e1kum\u00e1l]]'', Ragnar's death-song, an old and mysterious skaldic poem\n\nIn her commentary on Saxo's ''[[Gesta Danorum]]'', Davidson notes that Saxo's coverage of Ragnar's legend in book IX of the ''Gesta'' appears to be an attempt to consolidate many of the confusing and contradictory events and stories known to the chronicler into the reign of one king, Ragnar. That is why many acts ascribed to Ragnar in the ''Gesta'' can be associated, through other sources, with various figures, some of whom are more historically tenable.<ref>Davidson p. 277</ref>\n\nThe candidates scholars like to associate with the \"historical Ragnar\" include:\n* the ''Reginherus'' or ''Ragnar'' who [[Siege of Paris (845)|besieged Paris]] in 845\n* the Danish King [[Horik I]] (d. 854)\n* King [[Reginfrid]] (d. 814), a king who ruled part of Denmark in tandem with his brother [[Harald Klak]], but was expelled by Horik I and his brothers and later fell in a battle against them\n* possibly the [[Rognvald Eysteinsson|Ragnall]] (Ragnvald or Ragnar) of the [[Irish Annals]]{{sfn|Davidson|1980|p=277}}\n\nAttempts to reliably associate the legendary Ragnar with one or several of those men have failed because of the difficulty in reconciling the various accounts and their chronology. But the tradition of a Viking hero named Ragnar (or similar) who wreaked havoc in mid-[[9th-century]] Europe and who fathered many famous sons is remarkably persistent, and some aspects of it are strengthened by relatively reliable sources, such as Irish historical tradition and, indirectly, the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]''.<ref>Smyth (1977).</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n{{in popular culture|date=January 2020}}\nRagnar Lodbrok features prominently in the following works:\n* [[Edwin Atherstone]]'s 1830 novel ''Sea-Kings in England''.\n* [[Edison Marshall]]'s 1951 novel ''The Viking''.<ref>Historical Novels.info [http://www.historicalnovels.info/Viking.html]</ref>\n* \"[[:fr:Ragnar le Viking|Ragnar le Viking]]\", a 1955 comic book feature written by Jean Ollivier with art by Eduardo Teixeira Coelho, that ran in the French ''[[Pif Gadget|Vaillant]]'' magazine up to 1969.<ref>BD oubli\u00e9es [https://www.bdoubliees.com/vaillantpif/series5/ragnar.htm]</ref>\n* Richard Parker's 1957 historical novel ''The Sword of [[Ganelon]]'' explores the character of Ragnar, his sons, and Viking raiding culture.<ref>Kirkus Review [https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/richard-parker-4/the-sword-of-ganelon/]</ref>\n* The 1958 film ''[[The Vikings (1958 film)|The Vikings]]'' based on Marshall's novel, in which Ragnar, played by [[Ernest Borgnine]], is captured by King \u00c6lla and cast into a pit of wolves; a son named Einar {{sic}}, played by [[Kirk Douglas]], vows revenge and conquers [[Northumbria]] with help from half-brother (and sworn enemy) Eric (played by [[Tony Curtis]]), who also had much to avenge upon King Aella.\n* [[Harry Harrison (writer)|Harry Harrison]]'s 1993 alternative history novel ''[[The Hammer and the Cross]]'' depicts Ragnar being shipwrecked, captured and executed, as well as his sons' revenge.<ref>Publisher's Weekly, review [https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-312-85439-3]</ref>\n* [[History (Canadian TV network)|History]]'s popular 2013 TV series ''[[Vikings (2013 TV series)|Vikings]]''. Australian actor [[Travis Fimmel]] played the lead character of Ragnar Lothbrok for the first four seasons.\n* Various [[strategy video game]]s with a historical setting, including ''[[Civilization III: Play the World]]'', ''[[Medieval: Total War]]'', ''[[Civilization IV: Warlords]]'', ''[[Age of Empires II: The Forgotten]]'' and ''[[Crusader Kings II]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of legendary kings of Denmark]]\n* [[List of legendary kings of Sweden]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<!--unused<ref name=\"Saxo9\">{{cite web |title=The Danish History, Book Nine |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/saxo/saxo09.htm |website=www.sacred-texts.com}}</ref>-->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{citation | last = Duckett | first = Eleanor S|title=Carolingian Portraits: A Study in the Ninth Century|year=1988|publisher = University of Michigan|isbn=978-0-472-06157-0|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pQkkYygCpbUC&printsec=frontcover | mode=cs1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Harrison |first=Mark |year=1993 |title=Viking Hersir 793\u20131066 AD |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]] |isbn=978-1-85532-318-6| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Holman |first=Katherine |title=Historical dictionary of the Vikings |year=2003 |publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]] |location=[[Lanham, Maryland]] |isbn=978-0-8108-4859-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation | last = Jones | first = Gwyn|title= A History of the Vikings|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University| isbn = 978-0-19-280134-0 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lD74bDG3O5oC&printsec=frontcover | mode=cs1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kohn |first=George C. |year=2006 |title=Dictionary of Wars |isbn=978-1-4381-2916-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Magnusson |first=Magnus |year=2008 |title=The Vikings: Voyagers of Discovery and Plunder |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84603-340-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation | last = Sawyer | first = PH |title=Illustrated History of the Vikings|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University|isbn = 978-0-19-285434-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nJqf8e1vHFgC&printsec=frontcover | mode=cs1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Davidson|1980}}\n|author=Saxo Grammaticus |authorlink1=Saxo Grammaticus |editor1-first=Hilda Roderick Ellis |editor1-last=Davidson |editor1-link=Hilda Ellis Davidson |others=Translated by Peter Fisher |title=[[Gesta Danorum]] |trans-title=Saxo Grammaticus: The history of the Danes: books I\u2013IX |volume=1 & 2 |origyear=1979|year=1980 |publisher=[[D. S. Brewer]] |location=[[Cambridge]] |at=Chapter introduction commentaries |isbn=978-0-85991-502-1}}\n* {{cite book |year=c. 1200 |title=[[S\u00f6gubrot af nokkrum fornkonungum]] |ref={{harvid|S\u00f6gubrot|1200}}}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Sprague|2007}}\n|last=Sprague |first=Martina |authorlink= |title=Norse Warfare: the Unconventional Battle Strategies of the Ancient Vikings |publisher=Hippocrene Books |year=2007 |location=New York |url=https://archive.org/details/norsewarfareunco0000spra |url-access=registration\n|isbn=0-7818-1176-7}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Forte, Angelo, Richard Oram, and Frederik Pedersen (2005). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_vEd859jvk0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_navlinks_s#v=onepage&q=&f=false Viking Empires]''. Cambridge University Press, {{ISBN|0-521-82992-5}}.\n* \"Kr\u00e1kum\u00e1l\", ''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 17 (2001), p. 299-302. \n* {{cite book |first=Rory |last=McTurk |author-link=Rory McTurk |title=Studies in Ragnars saga lo\u00f0br\u00f3kar and Its Major Scandinavian Analogues |year=1991 |series=Medium Aevum Monographs |volume=15 |place=Oxford |isbn=0-907570-08-9}}\n* \"Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa\", ''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 24 (2003), p. 112-117.\n* \"Ragnars saga Lo\u00f0br\u00f3kar\",''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 24 (2003), p. 108-112.\n* [[Margaret Schlauch|Schlauch, Margaret]] (transl.) (1964). ''The Saga of the Volsungs: the Saga of Ragnar Lodbrok Together with the Lay of Kraka.'' New York: American Scandinavian Foundation.\n* Smyth, Alfred P. (1977). ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press.\n* Storm, Gustav (1877), \"Ragnar Lodbrok og Lodbrokss\u00f8nnerne; studie i dansk oldhistorie og nordisk sagnhistorie\", ''Historisk Tidskrift'' II:1 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639;view=1up;seq=419] \n* Strerath-Bolz, Ulrike (1993). [http://userpage.fu-berlin.de/~alvismal/2rory.pdf Review of [[Rory McTurk]], ''Studies in \"Ragnars saga lo\u00f0br\u00f3kar\" and Its Major Scandinavian Analogues''], ''Alv\u00edssm\u00e1l'' 2: 118\u201319.\n* Todd, James H. (1867), ''Coghad Gaedhel re Gallaibh'', London: Longman [https://archive.org/details/cogadhgaedhelreg00todd/page/26/mode/2up]\n* {{cite book |first=Ben |last=Waggoner |title=The Sagas of Ragnar Lodbrok |publisher=The Troth |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-578-02138-6}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Norse mythology}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ragnar Lodbrok}}\n[[Category:Danish legendary figures]]\n[[Category:English heroic legends]]\n[[Category:Heroes in Norse myths and legends]]\n[[Category:Mythological kings of Denmark]]\n[[Category:People whose existence is disputed]]\n[[Category:Ragnar Lodbrok| ]]\n[[Category:Semi-legendary kings of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Viking Age monarchs]]\n[[Category:V\u00f6lsung cycle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Harley MS 2278, folio 39r excerpt.jpg|thumb|Lothbrocus and his sons [[Ivar the Boneless|Ivar]] and [[Ubba]]. 15th-century miniature in ''[[Harleian Library|Harley]] MS 2278'', folio 39r.]]\n'''Ragnar Lodbrok''' or '''Lothbrok''' ({{lang-non|Ragnarr Lo\u00f0br\u00f3k}}, \"Ragnar shaggy breeches\", [[Modern Icelandic]]: ''Ragnar Lo\u00f0br\u00f3k'') in [[saga]]s  is a historically dubious{{sfn|Magnusson|2008|p=106}} legendary {{sfn|Harrison|1993|p=16}} [[Norsemen|Norse]] [[Viking]] hero, as well as Danish and Swedish King, known from [[Viking Age]] [[Old Norse poetry]], Icelandic stories, and near contemporary chronicles. According to the traditional literature, Ragnar Lodbrok distinguished himself by many raids against the [[British Isles]] and [[Holy Roman Empire]] during the 9th century. According to the sagas Ragnar Lodbrok's father was the [[Legendary Kings of Sweden|legendary Swedish king]] [[Sigurd Ring]]. <ref>https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/Ragnar-Lothbrok/</ref>\n\n== Accounts ==\n=== The Icelandic Sagas ===\nAccording to the ''[[Saga of Ragnar Lodbrok]]'', ''[[Tale of Ragnar's sons]]'', ''[[Heimskringla]]'', ''[[Hervarar Saga]]'', ''[[S\u00f6gubrot]]'', and many other Icelandic sources, Ragnar was the son of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] king [[Sigurd Ring]]. Nearly all of the sagas agree that [[Randver]] was Sigurd's father, with the ''[[Hervarar saga]]'' citing his wife as \u00c5sa, the daughter of King [[Harald Granraude|Harald of the Red Moustache]] from Norway. The accounts further tell that Randver was a grandson of the legendary Scandinavian king [[Ivar Vidfamne]] by his daughter Aud (whom the ''[[Hervarar saga]]'' calls Alfhild).<ref>Tolkien, Christopher, & Turville-Petre, G. (eds) (1956) ''Hervarar Saga ok Heidreks''. London: Viking Society for Northern Research, p. 68-9. [http://www.vsnrweb-publications.org.uk/Text%20Series/Hervarar%20saga%20ok%20heidreks.pdf]\n</ref> After the death of king [[Ivar Vidfamne]], Aud's eldest son by the [[Danes|Danish]] king [[Hr\u0153rekr Ringslinger]], Harald, conquered all of his grandfather's territory and became known as [[Harald Wartooth]]. Harald's nephew [[Sigurd Ring]] became the chief king of Sweden after Randver's death (Denmark according to ''Hervarar saga''), presumably as the subking of Harald. Sigurd and Harald fought the Battle of the Br\u00e1vellir ([[Br\u00e5valla]]) on the plains of [[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]], where Harald and many of his men died. Sigurd then ruled Sweden and Denmark (being sometimes identified with a Danish king [[Sigfred]] who ruled from about 770 until his death prior to 804). He sired a son with the Norwegian princess Alfhild of the semi-mythical \u00c1lfar people, Ragnar Lodbrok, who succeeded him.<ref>''S\u00f6gubrot'', Chapter 10 [https://web.archive.org/web/20100908081803/http://www.oe.eclipse.co.uk/nom/Fragment.htm]</ref> [[Eysteinn Beli]], who according to the ''[[Hervarar Saga]]'' was Harald Wartooth's son, ruled Sweden sometime after Sigurd until he was slain by the sons of Ragnar and [[Aslaug]].<ref>''The Tale of Ragnar's Sons'', Chapter 2 [http://www.germanicmythology.com/FORNALDARSAGAS/ThattrRagnarsSonar.html]</ref> \n\nIn their accounts of his reign, the Icelandic sagas tell more about Ragnar's marriages than about feats of warfare. According to the ''[[Sogubrot|S\u00f6gubrot]]'', \"he was the biggest and fairest of men that human eyes have seen, and he was like his mother in appearance and took after her kin\".<ref>''S\u00f6gubrot'', Chapter 10 [[https://web.archive.org/web/20100908081803/http://www.oe.eclipse.co.uk/nom/Fragment.htm]</ref> He first killed a giant snake that guarded the abode of the [[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland|East Geatic]] jarl's daughter [[Thora Borgarhjort]], thereby winning her as his wife. The unusual protective clothes that Ragnar wore, when attacking the serpent, earned him the nickname Lodbrok (\"shaggy breeches\"). His sons with Thora were [[Erik Weatherhat|Erik]] and Agnar. After Thora died, he discovered [[Aslaug|Kr\u00e1ka]], a woman of outstanding beauty and wisdom living with a poor peasant couple in [[Norway]], and married her. This marriage resulted in the sons [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], [[Hvitserk]], Ragnvald and [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]].<ref>''Ragnars Saga Lodbrokar'', Chapters 4 and 7 [https://www.snerpa.is/net/forn/ragnar.htm]</ref> Kr\u00e1ka was later revealed to actually be [[Aslaug]], a secret daughter of the renowned hero [[Sigurd|Sigurd Fafnesbane]]. As the sons grew up to become renowned warriors, Ragnar, not wishing to be outdone, resolved to conquer [[England]] with merely two ships. He was however defeated by superior English forces and was thrown into a snake pit to die in agony.<ref>''Ragnars Saga Lodbrokar'', Chapter 15 [https://www.snerpa.is/net/forn/ragnar.htm]</ref> The ''[[Saga of Ragnar Lodbrok]]'', ''[[Tale of Ragnar's Sons]]'', and ''[[Heimskringla]]'' all tell of the [[Great Heathen Army]] that invaded England at around 866, led by the sons of Ragnar Lodbrok to wreak revenge against King [[\u00c6lla of Northumbria]] who is told to have captured and executed Ragnar.\n\n=== Danish sources ===\nThe ''[[Chronicon Roskildense]]'' (c. 1138) mentions Lodbrok (Lothpardus) as father to the utterly cruel Norse King Ywar (rex crudelissimus Normannorum Ywar) and his brothers, Inguar (a double of Ywar), Ubbi, Byorn and Ulf, who rule the northern peoples. They call on the various Danish petty kings to help them ruin the realm of the [[Franks]]. Ywar successfully attacks the kingdoms of [[Great Britain|Britain]], though not as an act of revenge as in the Icelandic sagas.<ref>''Chronicon Roskildense'', p. 16[https://archive.org/stream/scriptoresminore112gert#page/16/mode/2up]</ref> The chronicle of [[Sven Aggesen]] (c. 1190) is the first Danish text that mentions the full name, Regnerus Lothbrogh. His son Sigurd invades Denmark and kills its king, whose daughter he marries as he takes over the throne. Their son in turn is [[Hardeknud I|Knut]], ancestor of the later Danish kings.<ref>Sven Aggeson, p. 106[https://archive.org/stream/scriptoresminore112gert#page/106/mode/2up]</ref> \n\nNeither of these sources mentions Ragnar Lodbrok as a Danish ruler. The first to do so is [[Saxo Grammaticus]] in his work ''[[Gesta Danorum]]'' (c. 1200). This work mixes Norse legend with data about Danish history derived from the chronicle of [[Adam of Bremen]] (c. 1075).<ref>Storm (1877), p. 387-9 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639&view=1up&seq=399] </ref> Here Ragnar's father Sigurd Ring is a Norwegian prince married to a Danish princess, and different from the victor of Br\u00e1vellir (who had flourished about thirteen generations earlier). Sigurd Ring and his cousin and rival Ring (that is, [[Sigfred (Danish king 812)|Sigfred]] and [[Anulo]] of recorded history, d. 812) are both killed in battle, whereupon Ragnar is elevated to the Danish kingship (identified by Saxo with [[Reginfrid|Ragnfred]], d. 814<ref>Storm (1877), p. 399 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639&view=1up&seq=411]</ref>).<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 539-41 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/541]</ref>  His first deed is the defeat of the Swedish king Fr\u00f6, who has killed Ragnar's grandfather. Ragnar is assisted in this by the ferocious shield-maiden [[Ladgerda]], whom he forces to marry him. In this marriage he sires the son Fridleif and two daughters.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 542-3 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/543]</ref>  He later repudiates the unreliable Ladgerda and instead wins the daughter of the Swedish king [[Herrau\u00f0r]], [[Thora Borgarhjort|Thora]], after killing two venomous giant snakes that guard her residence. His sons with Thora are Radbard, Dunvat, [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], Agnar and [[Ivar the Boneless]]. From a non-marital affair with the daughter of one Esbj\u00f8rn, Ragnar begets [[Ubba|Ubbe]], while his last marriage with Svanlaug produces another three sons, Ragnvald, [[Eric Weatherhat]] and [[Hvitserk]].<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 545, 550 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/550]</ref> \n\nThe sons were installed as sub-kings in various conquered territories. Ragnar led a Viking expedition to England and slew its king Hama, proceeding to kill the earls of [[Scotland]] and install Sigurd Snake-in-the Eye and Radbard as governors. Norway was also subjugated, and Fridleif was made ruler there and in [[Orkney]]. Later on, Ragnar with three sons invaded Sweden where a new king called S\u00f6rle had appeared and withheld the heritage of Thora's sons. S\u00f6rle and his army were massacred and Bj\u00f6rn Ironside was installed on the throne.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 551 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/551]</ref>  Some time later Bj\u00f6rn was put in charge of Norway, while Ragnar appointed another son, Eric Weatherhat, as ruler in Sweden; he was subsequently killed by a certain [[Eysteinn Beli|Eysteinn]]. One of the sons, Ubbe, revolted against his father at the instigation of his maternal grandfather Esbj\u00f8rn, and could only be defeated and captured with utmost effort.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 557 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/557]</ref> Saxo moreover tells of repeated expeditions to the [[British Isles]], one of which cost the lives of Dunvat and Radbard. \u00c6lla, son of Hama, expelled Ragnar's sub-ruler Ivar the Boneless from England with the help of the Galli (Gaill, Hiberno-Norse?<ref>Smyth (1977).</ref>) and remained a persistent enemy.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 560-1 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/560]</ref> Finally, the [[Scythians]] were forced to accept Hvitserk as their ruler. In the end Hvitserk was treacherously captured by the [[Hellespontus (province)|Hellespontian]] prince Daxon and burnt alive with his own admission. Hearing this, Ragnar led an expedition to [[Kievan Rus']] and captured Daxon who was curiously spared and exiled.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 558-9 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/558]</ref> \n\nUnlike the Icelandic sources, Saxo's account of Ragnar Lodbrok's reign is largely a catalog of successful Viking invasions over an enormous geographical area. Among the seaborne expeditions was one against the [[Bjarmians]] and [[Finns]] ([[Sami people|Saami]]) in the Arctic north. The Bjarmian use of magic spells caused foul weather and the sudden death of many Danish invaders, and the Finnish archers on skis turned out to be a formidable foe. Eventually these two tribes were put to flight and the Bjarmian king was slain.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 558-9 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/554]</ref> The historical king [[Harald Klak]] is by Saxo (based on a passage in Adam's chronicle) made into another persistent enemy of Ragnar, who several times incited the [[Jutes]] and [[Sk\u00e5ne|Scanians]] to rebel, but was regularly defeated. After the last victory over Harald, Ragnar learned that King \u00c6lla had massacred Ragnar's men on [[Ireland]]. Incensed, he attacked the English king with his fleet but was captured and thrown into the snake pit, similar to the Icelandic sagas. In spite of all his praise for Ragnar Lodbrok, Saxo also considers his fate as God's rightful vengeance for the contempt he had shown the Christian religion.<ref>Saxo Grammaticus, Book 9, p. 562-3 [https://archive.org/details/ninebooksofdanis02saxouoft/page/563]</ref>\n\n=== Poetic and epigraphic sources ===\nWhile the narrative Norse sources date from the 12th and 13th centuries, there are also many older poems that mention him and his kin. The ''[[Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa]]'', ostensibly composed by [[Bragi Boddason]] in the 9th century, praises a Ragnar, son of Sigurd, for a richly decorated shield that the poet has received. The shield depicts the assault on [[Ermanaric|J\u00f6rmunrek]], the [[Hja\u00f0ningav\u00edg]] tale, the ploughing of [[Gefjon]], and [[Thor]]'s struggle with the [[Midgard Serpent]]. Recent scholarship has suggested that the poem is in fact from c. 1000 and celebrates the Norse reconquest of England. The four tales depicted on the shield would then symbolize four aspects of the Lodbrok saga (the initial defeat of the sons of Lodbrok in England due to recklessness, Ivar the Boneless's deceitful approach to King \u00c6lla, Ivar's cunning snatching of land from \u00c6lla, Ragnar's struggle against the giant serpent in order to win Thora).<ref>\"Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa\", ''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 24, p. 115.</ref> The ''Knutsdrapa'' of [[Sigvat Thordarson]] (c. 1038) mentions the death of \u00c6lla at the hands of Ivar in [[York]], who \"carved the eagle on \u00c6lla's back\".<ref>Smyth (1977), p. 193-4.</ref> From this the story of the atrocious revenge of Lodbrok's sons already seems to be present. The reference to a \"[[blood eagle]]\" punishment has however been much debated by modern scholars.<ref>[[Rory McTurk]], \"Kings and kingship in Viking Northumbria\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20080926171200/http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm]</ref> Another lay, ''[[Krakumal]]'', put in the mouth of the dying Ragnar in the snake pit, recounts the exploits of Ragnar and mentions battles over a wide geographical area, several relating to the British isles. The poem's name, \"Kr\u00e1ka's lay\", alludes to Ragnar's wife's [[Aslaug|Kr\u00e1ka]],<ref>\"Kr\u00e1kum\u00e1l\", ''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 17 (2001), p. 299-300.</ref> though modern philologists commonly date it to the 12th century in its present form.<ref>Smyth (1977), p. 73-80.</ref> \n\nThere is one runic inscription mentioning Lodbrok, carved on the prehistorical tumulus of [[Maeshowe]] on [[Orkney]] in the early 12th century. It reads: \"This howe was built a long time before Lodbrok's. Her sons, they were bold; scarcely ever were there such tall men of their hands\".<ref>Smyth (1977), p. 81.</ref> The expression \"her sons\" has given rise to the theory that Lodbrok was originally thought of as a woman,<ref>Gustav Storm (1877), \"Ragnar Lodbrok og Lodbrokss\u00f8nnerne; studie i dansk oldhistorie og nordisk sagnhistorie\", ''Historisk Tidskrift'' II:1 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639;view=1up;seq=419]</ref> mother of the historically known sons.<ref>[[Rory McTurk]], \"Kings and kingship in Viking Northumbria\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20080926171200/http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm]; </ref>\n\n=== Frankish accounts of a 9th-century Viking leader named Ragnar ===\nThe [[Siege of Paris (845)|Siege of Paris]] and the Sack of Paris of 845 was the culmination of a Viking invasion of the kingdom of the [[West Francia|West Franks]]. The Viking forces were led by a Norse chieftain named \"Reginherus\", or Ragnar.{{Sfn | Kohn | 2006 | p = 588}}  This Ragnar has often been tentatively identified with the legendary saga figure Ragnar Lodbrok,<ref>''Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde'', Vol. 24, p. 111, 113, 116.</ref> but the accuracy of this is disputed by historians.{{Sfn | Jones | 2001 | p = 212}}{{Sfn | Sprague | 2007 | p = 225}} Ragnar Lodbrok is also sometimes identified with a Ragnar who was awarded land in [[Torhout]], [[Flanders]], by [[Charles the Bald]] in about 841 but eventually lost the land as well as the favour of the King.{{Sfn | Sawyer | 2001 | p = 40}}  Ragnar's Vikings raided [[Rouen]] on their way up the Seine in 845  and in response to the invasion, determined not to let the royal [[Basilica of St Denis|Abbey of Saint-Denis]] (near Paris) be destroyed, Charles assembled an army which he divided into two parts, one for each side of the river.{{Sfn | Duckett | 1988 | p = 181}}{{Sfn | Jones | 2001 |  p = 212}} Ragnar attacked and defeated one of the divisions of the smaller Frankish army, took 111 of their men as prisoners and hanged them on an island on the Seine to honour the [[Norse religion|Norse god]] [[Odin]], as well as to incite terror in the remaining Frankish forces.{{Sfn | Kohn | 2006 | p = 588}}{{Sfn | Jones | 2001 | p = 212}} Ragnar's fleet made it back to his overlord, the Danish King [[Horik I]], but Ragnar soon died from a violent illness that also spread in Denmark.<ref>Storm (1877), p. 438 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044105191639&view=1up&seq=450]</ref>\n\n=== Later continental accounts ===\nAmong the oldest texts to mention the name Lodbrok is the Norman history of [[William of Jumi\u00e8ges]] from c. 1070. According to William, the Danish kings of old had the custom to expel the younger sons from the kingdom to have them out of the way. At a time it happened that King [[Ragnar Lodbrok|Lodbrok]] succeeded his unnamed father on the Danish throne. After gaining power he honoured the said custom and ordered his junior son [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]] to leave his realm. Bj\u00f6rn thus left Denmark with a considerable fleet and started to ravage in [[West Francia]] and later the [[Mediterranean]].<ref>Guillaume de Jumi\u00e8ges, ''Histoire des ducs de Normandie'', p. 11-3 [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015013753564;view=1up;seq=23]</ref> Roughly contemporary with William is [[Adam of Bremen]] whose history of the [[Archbishopric of Hamburg|Archbishopric of Hamburg-Bremen]] contains many traditions about Viking Age Scandinavia. In a passage referring to the Viking raids of the late 9th century, he mentions the Danish or Norse pirates Horich, Orwig, Gotafrid, Rudolf and Inguar (Ivar). This Ivar is in particular seen as a cruel persecutor of Christians, and a son of Lodbrok (Inguar, filius Lodparchi).<ref>Adam von Bremen, ''Hamburgische Kirchengeschichte'', p. 39-40[https://archive.org/stream/adamvonbremenham00adam#page/40/mode/2up]</ref>\n\n=== Anglo-Saxon and Irish accounts of the father of Ivar and Halfdan ===\nAccording to the contemporary ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' and [[Asser]]'s ''Life of Alfred'', in 878 the \"brother of Hingwar and Healfden\", with a naval fleet, a contingent of the [[Great Heathen Army]] invaded [[Devon]] in England and fought the [[Battle of Cynwit]]. There the Vikings lost, their king slain and many dead, with few escaping to their ships. After the battle the [[Saxons]] took great plunder, and among other things the banner called \"Raven\".<ref>Garmonsway, G.N. (1972), ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''. London: Dent, p. 75-7.</ref> The early 12th century ''[[Annals of St Neots]]'' further state that ''\"they say that the three sisters of Hingwar and Hubba, daughters of Lodebroch (Lodbrok), wove that flag and got it ready in one day. They say, moreover, that in every battle, wherever the flag went before them, if they were to gain the victory a live crow would appear flying on the middle of the flag; but if they were doomed to be defeated it would hang down motionless, and this was often proved to be so.\"''<ref>Garmonsway, G.N. (1972), ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''. London: Dent, p. 77.</ref>\nThis is among the earlier references to the legendary hero Ragnar Lodbrok.\n\nThe Irish ''[[Cogad G\u00e1edel re Gallaib]]'' from the 12th century, with information deriving from earlier annals, mentions king Halfdan (d. 877) under the name \"mac Ragnaill\".<ref>James Todd (1867), ''Cogadh Gaedhel re Gallaibh'', London: Longman, p. 27 [https://archive.org/details/cogadhgaedhelreg00todd/page/26/mode/2up]</ref> The form Ragnall may refer to either Ragnvald or Ragnar, and the entry is a strong indication that the name of Ivar's and Halfdan's father was really Ragnar or a similar name.<ref>Smyth, Alfred P. (1977) ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, p. 263, 279.</ref> The early 11th century ''[[Three Fragments]]'' contains a passage that gives a semi-legendary background to the capture of York by the Vikings in 866. The two younger sons of Halfdan, King of [[Lochlann]], expelled the eldest son Ragnall who sailed to the [[Orkney islands]] with his three sons and settled there. Two of the sons later raided the English and [[Franks]], proceeding to plunder in the Mediterranean. One of them learnt from a vision that Ragnall had fought a battle where the third son had been slain and in which he himself had most likely perished. The two Viking sons then returned home with a lot of dark-skinned captives.<ref>Smyth, Alfred P. (1977) ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, p. 62.</ref> It has been hypothesized that this is an Irish version of ''[[Ragnar Lodbrok's saga]]'', the Mediterranean expedition being a historical event taking place in 859-61.<ref>Smyth, Alfred P. (1977) ''Scandinavian kings in the British Isles 850-880''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, p. 64-5.</ref>\n\n== Ragnar's sons ==\n[[File:Rayner Lothbroc Saga by Norstedts 1880.jpg|thumb|upright|The saga as published by [[Norstedts]] in a large-size illustrated version (1880).]]\nThe [[Great Heathen Army]] is said to have been led by the sons of Ragnar Lodbrok, to wreak revenge against King [[\u00c6lla of Northumbria]] who had previously executed Ragnar by casting him into a pit full of venomous snakes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ancient-origins.net/history-famous-people/ragnar-lothbrok-ferocious-viking-hero-became-myth-008177|title=Ragnar Lothbrok: The Ferocious Viking Hero that Became a Myth|last=Karasavvas|first=Theodoros|work=Ancient Origins|access-date=28 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> Among the organizers were at least some of the brothers [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Ubba]], [[Halfdan Ragnarsson|Halfdan]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], [[Hvitserk]], and [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]], all of which are known as historical figures, save the slightly more dubious [[Hvitserk]].{{sfn|Holman|2003|p=220}} Ivar the Boneless was the leader of the Great Heathen Army from 865 to 870, but he disappears from English historical accounts after 870.<ref> Forte, Angelo; Oram, Richard; Pedersen, Frederik (30 May 2005). Viking Empires (First ed.). Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9780521829922}}</ref> The Anglo-Saxon chronicler [[\u00c6thelweard (historian)|\u00c6thelweard]] records Ivar's death as 870.<ref>Giles, J. A., ed. (10 September 2010). Six Old English Chronicles: Ethelwerd's Chronicle, Asser's Life Of Alfred, Geoffrey Of Monmouth's British History, Gildas, Nennius And Richard Of Cirencester. Kessinger Publishing, LLC. {{ISBN|9781163125991}}</ref> [[Halfdan Ragnarsson]] became the leader of the Great Heathen Army in about 870 and he led it in an invasion of Wessex.<ref>Forte, A; Oram, RD; Pedersen, F (2005). Viking Empires. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-82992-2}}. p. 72</ref> A great number of Viking warriors arrived from Scandinavia, as part of the Great Summer Army, led by King [[Bagsecg]] of Denmark, bolstering the ranks of Halfdan's army.<ref>Hooper, Nicholas Hooper; Bennett, Matthew (1996). The Cambridge Illustrated Atlas of Warfare: the Middle Ages. Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-44049-1}}. p.22</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'', the Danes battled the West Saxons nine times, including the [[Battle of Ashdown]] on 8 January 871, where Bagsecg was killed.<ref>Costambeys, M (2004). \"H\u00e1lfdan (d. 877)\". Oxford Dictionary of National Biography. Oxford University Press. {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/49260}}</ref> Halfdan accepted a truce from the future [[Alfred the Great]], newly crowned king of Wessex.<ref>Forte, A; Oram, RD; Pedersen, F (2005). Viking Empires. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-82992-2}}. pp. 72\u201373</ref> After Bagsecg's death Halfdan was the only remaining king of the invading host. He may also have been a King of part of Denmark ([[Jutland]]?), since a co-ruler [[Sigfred and Halfdan|Halfdan]] is mentioned in Frankish sources in 873.<ref>''Die Jahrb\u00fccher von Fulda und Xanten'', p. 62 [https://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb10015821_00076.html]</ref> According to late sagas Bj\u00f6rn Ironside became King of Sweden and Uppsala, although this presents chronological inconsistencies.<ref>Carl Bernadotte et al. (1956), ''Sveriges hundra konungar''. Stockholm: Biblioteksb\u00f6cker, p. 81. </ref> Bj\u00f6rn had two sons, [[Erik Bj\u00f6rnsson|Erik]] and [[Refil Bj\u00f6rnsson]]. His son Erik became the next king of Sweden, and was succeeded in turn by [[Erik Refilsson]], the son of Refil.<ref>Tolkien, Christopher, & Turville-Petre, G. (eds) (1956) ''Hervarar Saga ok Heidreks''. London: Viking Society for Northern Research, p. 69. [http://www.vsnrweb-publications.org.uk/Text%20Series/Hervarar%20saga%20ok%20heidreks.pdf]\n</ref> Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye is perhaps the same person as [[Sigfred and Halfdan|Sigfred]], brother of Halfdan, who was king in Denmark together with Halfdan in 873.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm ''Kings and kingship in Viking Northumbria'', by [[Rory McTurk]] (University of Leeds)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926171200/http://www.dur.ac.uk/medieval.www/sagaconf/mcturk.htm |date=26 September 2008 }}</ref> According to the sagas Sigurd became King of [[Zealand]], [[Sk\u00e5ne]] and the lesser Danish Isles.<ref>''The Tale of Ragnar's Sons'', Chapter 3 [http://www.germanicmythology.com/FORNALDARSAGAS/ThattrRagnarsSonar.html]</ref> Sigfred-Sigurd possibly succeeded his brother Halfdan as King of entire Denmark in about 877, and may be the Viking king Sigfred who was killed in [[West Francia]] in 887.<ref>P.A. Munch (1852), ''Det norske Folks Historie'', Vol. I:1. Christiania: Tonsberg, p. 642-8.</ref>\n\n== Sources and historical accuracy ==\n[[File:Rayner Lothbroc & Kraka by August Malmstr\u00f6m c 1880.jpg|upright|thumb|Ragnar receives [[Aslaug|Kr\u00e1ka]] (Aslaug), as imagined by [[August Malmstr\u00f6m]].]]\n[[File:Ragnar Lodbroks d\u00f6d by Hugo Hamilton.jpg|thumb|right|19th-century artist's impression of \u00c6lla of Northumbria's execution of Ragnar Lodbrok]]\nWhereas Ragnar's sons [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Halfdan Ragnarsson]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Ironside]], [[Ubba|Ubbe]] and [[Sigurd Snake-in-the-Eye]] are historical figures, opinion regarding their father is divided. Modern academia regards most of the stories about him to be fiction. According to [[Hilda Ellis Davidson]], writing in 1979,\n\n<blockquote>Certain scholars in recent years have come to accept at least part of Ragnar's story as based on historical fact.<ref>Davidson p. 277</ref></blockquote> A generation later, however, Katherine Holman wrote in 2003: <blockquote>Although his sons are historical figures, there is no evidence that Ragnar himself ever lived and he seems to be an amalgam of historical figures and literary invention.<ref name=\"Z\">Holman 2003 p. 220</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe most significant medieval sources that mention Ragnar include:\n* Book IX of the ''[[Gesta Danorum]]'', a 12th-century work by the Christian Danish chronicler [[Saxo Grammaticus]]\n* the ''[[Tale of Ragnar's Sons|Tale of Ragnar's sons]]'' (''Ragnarssona \u00fe\u00e1ttr''), a [[legendary saga]]\n* the ''[[Tale of Ragnar Lothbrok ]]'', another saga, a sequel to the ''[[V\u00f6lsunga saga]]''\n* the ''[[Ragnarsdr\u00e1pa]]'', a [[skaldic poem]] of which only fragments remain, attributed to the 9th-century poet [[Bragi Boddason]]\n* the ''[[Kr\u00e1kum\u00e1l]]'', Ragnar's death-song, an old and mysterious skaldic poem\n\nIn her commentary on Saxo's ''[[Gesta Danorum]]'', Davidson notes that Saxo's coverage of Ragnar's legend in book IX of the ''Gesta'' appears to be an attempt to consolidate many of the confusing and contradictory events and stories known to the chronicler into the reign of one king, Ragnar. That is why many acts ascribed to Ragnar in the ''Gesta'' can be associated, through other sources, with various figures, some of whom are more historically tenable.<ref>Davidson p. 277</ref>\n\nThe candidates scholars like to associate with the \"historical Ragnar\" include:\n* the ''Reginherus'' or ''Ragnar'' who [[Siege of Paris (845)|besieged Paris]] in 845\n* the Danish King [[Horik I]] (d. 854)\n* King [[Reginfrid]] (d. 814), a king who ruled part of Denmark in tandem with his brother [[Harald Klak]], but was expelled by Horik I and his brothers and later fell in a battle against them\n* possibly the [[Rognvald Eysteinsson|Ragnall]] (Ragnvald or Ragnar) of the [[Irish Annals]]{{sfn|Davidson|1980|p=277}}\n\nAttempts to reliably associate the legendary Ragnar with one or several of those men have failed because of the difficulty in reconciling the various accounts and their chronology. But the tradition of a Viking hero named Ragnar (or similar) who wreaked havoc in mid-[[9th-century]] Europe and who fathered many famous sons is remarkably persistent, and some aspects of it are strengthened by relatively reliable sources, such as Irish historical tradition and, indirectly, the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]''.<ref>Smyth (1977).</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n{{in popular culture|date=January 2020}}\nRagnar Lodbrok features prominently in the following works:\n* [[Edwin Atherstone]]'s 1830 novel ''Sea-Kings in England''.\n* [[Edison Marshall]]'s 1951 novel ''The Viking''.<ref>Historical Novels.info [http://www.historicalnovels.info/Viking.html]</ref>\n* \"[[:fr:Ragnar le Viking|Ragnar le Viking]]\", a 1955 comic book feature written by Jean Ollivier with art by Eduardo Teixeira Coelho, that ran in the French ''[[Pif Gadget|Vaillant]]'' magazine up to 1969.<ref>BD oubli\u00e9es [https://www.bdoubliees.com/vaillantpif/series5/ragnar.htm]</ref>\n* Richard Parker's 1957 historical novel ''The Sword of [[Ganelon]]'' explores the character of Ragnar, his sons, and Viking raiding culture.<ref>Kirkus Review [https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/richard-parker-4/the-sword-of-ganelon/]</ref>\n* The 1958 film ''[[The Vikings (1958 film)|The Vikings]]'' based on Marshall's novel, in which Ragnar, played by [[Ernest Borgnine]], is captured by King \u00c6lla and cast into a pit of wolves; a son named Einar {{sic}}, played by [[Kirk Douglas]], vows revenge and conquers [[Northumbria]] with help from half-brother (and sworn enemy) Eric (played by [[Tony Curtis]]), who also had much to avenge upon King Aella.\n* [[Harry Harrison (writer)|Harry Harrison]]'s 1993 alternative history novel ''[[The Hammer and the Cross]]'' depicts Ragnar being shipwrecked, captured and executed, as well as his sons' revenge.<ref>Publisher's Weekly, review [https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-312-85439-3]</ref>\n* [[History (Canadian TV network)|History]]'s popular 2013 TV series ''[[Vikings (2013 TV series)|Vikings]]''. Australian actor [[Travis Fimmel]] played the lead character of Ragnar Lothbrok for the first four seasons.\n* Various [[strategy video game]]s with a historical setting, including ''[[Civilization III: Play the World]]'', ''[[Medieval: Total War]]'', ''[[Civilization IV: Warlords]]'', ''[[Age of Empires II: The Forgotten]]'' and ''[[Crusader Kings II]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of legendary kings of Denmark]]\n* [[List of legendary kings of Sweden]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<!--unused<ref name=\"Saxo9\">{{cite web |title=The Danish History, Book Nine |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/saxo/saxo09.htm |website=www.sacred-texts.com}}</ref>-->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{citation | last = Duckett | first = Eleanor S|title=Carolingian Portraits: A Study in the Ninth Century|year=1988|publisher = University of Michigan|isbn=978-0-472-06157-0|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pQkkYygCpbUC&printsec=frontcover | mode=cs1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Harrison |first=Mark |year=1993 |title=Viking Hersir 793\u20131066 AD |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]] |isbn=978-1-85532-318-6| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Holman |first=Katherine |title=Historical dictionary of the Vikings |year=2003 |publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]] |location=[[Lanham, Maryland]] |isbn=978-0-8108-4859-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation | last = Jones | first = Gwyn|title= A History of the Vikings|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University| isbn = 978-0-19-280134-0 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lD74bDG3O5oC&printsec=frontcover | mode=cs1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kohn |first=George C. |year=2006 |title=Dictionary of Wars |isbn=978-1-4381-2916-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Magnusson |first=Magnus |year=2008 |title=The Vikings: Voyagers of Discovery and Plunder |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84603-340-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation | last = Sawyer | first = PH |title=Illustrated History of the Vikings|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University|isbn = 978-0-19-285434-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nJqf8e1vHFgC&printsec=frontcover | mode=cs1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref={{harvid|Davidson|1980}}\n|author=Saxo Grammaticus |authorlink1=Saxo Grammaticus |editor1-first=Hilda Roderick Ellis |editor1-last=Davidson |editor1-link=Hilda Ellis Davidson |others=Translated by Peter Fisher |title=[[Gesta Danorum]] |trans-title=Saxo Grammaticus: The history of the Danes: books I\u2013IX |volume=1 & 2 |origyear=